<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no" ?>
<FinalDraft DocumentType="Script" Template="No" Version="6">

  <DocumentRef DateTime="20260406T193620" id="c9943917-4a17-48c6-87fd-ad66972d8977">
    <XRef DateTime="20260222T010105" id="a7ca2c80-0c55-4d64-aa4b-18bd8a2c69bf"/>
    <XRef DateTime="20260222T010807" id="cef447fc-5244-4d84-8378-770e72544dca"/>
    <XRef DateTime="20260223T010437" id="de863b85-bb25-42c7-8651-bbc0bbfdf9c0"/>
    <XRef DateTime="20260311T202801" id="07e80669-c4c0-4e99-b962-0ea7f1f9cddd"/>
    <XRef DateTime="20260311T225749" id="01e57726-08d4-4a2f-9a21-154a86facccb"/>
    <XRef DateTime="20260329T161923" id="554fef88-a57e-46f0-9334-05f40fe4c41a"/>
  </DocumentRef>

  <Content>
    <Paragraph Type="Transition" id="bfeec830-6644-45ce-a0bd-9513477d80de">
      <Text>COLD OPEN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3cd4e2fa-e941-4945-a086-70e2b873d51f">
      <Text>BLACK SCREEN.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f44230ab-36c2-4ffc-b2fa-cf402d181c22">
      <Text>Nothing.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1e808842-c6c0-49fc-8b5f-6cdece506295">
      <Text>Then—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="08a5bcbe-afe7-400c-915e-4f53435a500e">
      <Text>BEEEEEEEEEEP. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="946efa06-481d-43a2-be19-1a0f5e2df0c7">
      <Text>Not a fire alarm. Not a phone. Something lower. Something specific. Electronic. Bureaucratic. The sound of the state reminding you that it owns you.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d3c31c67-2763-48b2-8311-558130f9a8a2">
      <Text>Then a second alarm joins it. Same frequency. A half-beat behind. Point and counter point. The sound of the state reminding you that it owns your wife too.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="39b40540-b5b0-49da-a7fe-28dc70c1b6c9">
      <Text>Beneath both of them: tires sliding on asphalt where traction is becoming increasingly theoretical. The low groan of an engine performing well outside its comfort zone.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4466319b-df63-4579-b5b6-af4c96b4e832">
      <Text>Then—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="51445dc6-a3ac-4b5e-9f87-17c841dc6f9d">
      <Text>HUNTER (O.S.)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="1b2e3c03-b98e-4b66-97b2-6aafa73d3e88">
      <Text>(straining to sound professional)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="864e892d-6ff5-44c3-8326-0ff058b84ae6">
      <Text>Yes sir, Mr. Pruitt. I understand that. What I need from you is five minutes of professional courtesy and I need you to listen to what I'm telling you.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="97027397-c75e-4521-8977-d9fe9f075068">
      <Text>BEEEEEEEEEEP. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="447a4bc5-4f57-4624-a3df-694334625765">
      <Text>HUNTER (O.S.)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="f5d0d9e8-2ca9-4b88-8803-c963bc3d93f1">
      <Text>My name is Hunter Reid, I am counsel of record for Kevin McCort, I am in the physical presence of my client— as I'm sure you can tell from the alarms you can hear in the background—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="e14b5301-3d8f-4c51-841e-5081ebe6c456">
      <Text>MONITORING OFFICER (O.S.)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="80d11766-0366-4195-b975-972403d03f70">
      <Text>Is that two monitors?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="005f8ae8-8691-4067-a3e9-a55650f1b9e3">
      <Text>HUNTER (O.S.)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="17d88ba8-1023-433a-9e01-a22a07327fc3">
      <Text>(a beat)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="fdebf793-368e-40f5-ab48-280c1c7dc624">
      <Text>...It is, yes. The co-defendant is also present with us and in continuous transit toward the approved— But- No Sir, I am not in contact with her current representation at this time but I can very much assure you that her situation matches my clients as we are all in the same car. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="28501c42-15d5-44ea-ae32-e02e03d4b4f2">
      <Text>(breath)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="fcfcb3df-bf13-4327-8eab-1c753cb0eb91">
      <Text>Sir, this is exactly the situation I need you to understand, we have experienced some navigational difficulty specific to the rural geography of this area—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="c4181dcb-8cb8-4303-86fe-47fa6e30b16b">
      <Text>MONITORING OFFICER (O.S.)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="ec823b23-1cdd-49f2-9526-136697d5992e">
      <Text>What kind of navigational difficulty.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="a773366b-191b-4b24-9852-4e5f687e70d9">
      <Text>HUNTER (O.S.)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="68b8fd35-e073-4d8c-b510-6eb6fc3b6758">
      <Text>The kind where the road—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="8918da9c-832b-42c2-8eae-51b191c7ff93">
      <Text>(carefully)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="b8613e04-7936-4999-a766-9daf137c53a6">
      <Text>...changes character.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1826f359-7984-4350-8802-3ac4014d7d42">
      <Text>BEEEEEEEEEEP. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Right" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="5.50" RightIndent="7.10" SpaceBefore="12" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Transition" id="3218b813-bc19-40bc-bbd1-8c9c46028922">
      <Text>SMASH CUT TO:</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f58c3847-e9ed-45cd-b2b5-0edf2c1362de">
      <Text>TITLE CARD: THE PLAYBOY "Dead in the Water"</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="7bec7ac2-4ada-4f2f-9a9c-e98fa1372403">
      <SceneProperties Length="11 4/8" Page="2" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="HUNTER">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAMIE">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAZ">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="KEVIN">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="MONITORING OFFICER">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT/EXT. HUNTER'S CAR - NIGHT - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="27ebe251-e1a2-44c0-b454-d91e40ac1d77">
      <Text>The vehicle: a 1997 MANUAL TRANSMISSION HONDA CIVIC HATCHBACK in a color Honda once optimistically called "Heather Mist Metallic" that has since oxidized into something a crime scene investigator would describe as "consistent with gray." One side mirror hangs by a single zip tie. The pine tree air freshener dangling from the rearview has been dead so long it's become a philosophical statement.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="cff2239d-195a-46dc-ab66-730a8923bf31">
      <Text>Two ankle monitors are screaming in annoyingly barely offset alarms. The effect is not stereo. It is chaos.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2cd5492a-c5ab-403a-90b2-c51477cf361a">
      <Text>BEEEEEEEEEEP. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a7df6a20-e2c4-4cd0-acf7-b1cc8bae8474">
      <Text>HUNTER is behind the wheel. Same wrinkled shirt from the diner. Same coffee stain. He is driving with one hand alternating between the steering wheel and the gear shifter while holding JAZ'S PHONE against his ear with the other. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a7df6a20-e2c4-4cd0-acf7-b1cc8bae8474">
      <Text>This trick is only made harder by having to also navigate a two-lane road in rural New Jersey in the dark, on the phone defending his client, and the car is getting opinions about it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="af77ea9a-a9ad-4c37-a809-ffa476a6f96a">
      <Text>The car drifts. Corrects. Drifts again. A mailbox on a post appears suddenly in the headlights and vanishes.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="efd3b689-340b-4f1c-9dd9-a515ffbdd87b">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="10dd5e04-b56e-49f6-a0b6-9106062a86bb">
      <Text>KEVIN, passenger seat. The wrist is bare. The ankle is not. The ankle monitoring unit is SCREAMING, and Kevin is looking at it with the expression of a man who has never in his adult life not been unable to simply fix a problem by staring at it long enough.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="c82a4ac8-33d1-4631-8b9a-3a660333a649">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="4d93785b-6a43-4f7a-aec5-4326f4188eeb">
      <Text>Hunter.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="6cd3aefa-04b9-4647-bac8-154f66c8c078">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="882c1f7e-5ded-4744-bd4c-4ad59bdc97d3">
      <Text>(hand up, on the phone)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="bd2a5c3e-9b49-4d08-a5a7-befc4ac92736">
      <Text>One second—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="285ea67b-ae44-4ce4-bac0-e465f49999dd">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="015f95cf-dc3b-47ba-a745-d542519319e7">
      <Text>The alarm.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f7ca26b2-c417-4e27-b5d9-ffba0ba502ae">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="f4c59ca0-d69e-4322-a24b-587062ebdb47">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="71ca7495-b56e-469b-b02c-4ac9f3cf93bf">
      <Text>I know about the alarm.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="6618226d-6ffb-4229-8cba-378859768399">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="fa5d26c5-3ac1-4db0-a5f6-06a6090da5ad">
      <Text>It's been fourteen minutes.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="b507a6f3-a222-4d61-8d30-23a8727f7eca">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="8b5f6eed-de8a-4a24-82c0-6129f7f6fd3f">
      <Text>I am aware of how many minutes it has been, Kevin.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="46416aa4-a539-447d-9f2d-a2a5241af30a">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="c6af26d3-94e7-4aa2-87d1-adc96f9d1c6b">
      <Text>Then fix it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="6722a85e-3373-4bb7-91c8-3aa16999c835">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="688bd372-746b-4545-893e-637154b61826">
      <Text>That's what I'm doing.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="e0aa049a-6ba6-4283-ba24-2b65b61ab47b">
      <Text>(into phone, smooth)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="c9b09b32-2bff-44a0-9b80-d1f5da3f1929">
      <Text>Sir, yes— still here. I want to specifically address the language in Section 4(c) regarding what constitutes a boundary event versus a transit delay—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5383bf5b-b0ba-44b1-91f8-6798107b6ae7">
      <Text>The car drifts. Kevin grabs the dash.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d329a877-d4be-4def-833c-424b364323d2">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="ca2470a0-f3c0-4cdb-a6b5-56691458e6b4">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="af8ae88d-1b5b-456e-a8f2-49f32a945e4e">
      <Text>HUNTER—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="4601473f-611b-4c59-8bcb-cc7bbeadac71">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="93136b5b-3a4d-4d32-a0e5-8655e1e0783f">
      <Text>(wheel correction, into phone, without pause)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="8ffa04f5-3077-4d41-91ec-20eb1fb959a6">
      <Text>—because the distinction is material to how this notation appears in the record—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="11f02d3f-d1bb-411d-9cc3-1aed3f8ad2d8">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="b02a87a5-5f03-469d-81a8-d5625d274c43">
      <Text>You almost hit a MAILBOX—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="a2e2c5c7-d32d-4dbc-ba85-e4809b720991">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="c82cea65-1967-46d2-8062-926f132198ec">
      <Text>(hand over phone)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="90721afe-4432-4b49-a5bc-236cf4426538">
      <Text>I saw the mailbox.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="d2e67071-6f53-4a40-9b6b-7430e2f33ffd">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="b53662a4-e80a-47ad-b440-e0de450764ee">
      <Text>After you almost hit it!</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="3b55bd1b-ce22-49a8-89ea-8ff52fc3eed6">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="28fcf0ca-5a7f-41cc-8227-d01d4e066def">
      <Text>You want to fucking drive?!</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="0acb4427-2d74-4e4d-bee8-ae745f944011">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="2596b9b1-5750-4cad-a1a2-a97a6b57eeaf">
      <Text>It's a stick!</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="a97ed676-25fb-4290-b717-99ff094376ad">
      <Text>MONITORING OFFICER (O.S.)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="86631bee-3390-4898-bb3f-f852e83b499d">
      <Text>Mr. Reid—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3c31fc39-0640-469d-afb1-ca3b7dba5c27">
      <Text>Hunter gives Kevin a look that clearly communicates that the only reason Hunter hasn’t punched him in the face is the simple fact that Hunter does not currently have a free hand to do that.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="0eb1fe0e-42e8-456d-bc65-6a7b588e0b03">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="b94390fb-3cbb-4b63-8c81-c2d4dc0ec9e6">
      <Text>(back to phone)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="40c85303-c962-441d-8c79-9ad4239abb23">
      <Text>Sir, I'm here. Yes. We are on approach. Continuous approach.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d5b14c31-e5a6-40ef-920f-824767b26c3f">
      <Text>In the back seat:</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2a7f3a7a-f954-4aab-9a70-25ef2edea286">
      <Text>JANET, center of the bench. Lululemon. Hunter's jacket over her shoulders— it still smells like decisions made in the dark. She has it pulled tight around her because the Civic's heat works in the sense that it blows air, and the air is ambient.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a48717c8-4e8d-4d55-acb0-3f0e9841a3a1">
      <Text>Her left ankle is against the center hump, slightly forward, slightly away from Jaz beside her. The monitor on it is screaming with the same frequency as Kevin's. She is looking out the window at the dark nothing of Sussex County.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4c6a3011-25d0-4d2f-aa42-5d28ee0c2010">
      <Text>BEEEEEEEEEEP. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9b7624b4-beb4-4287-9eb0-f8af213c41df">
      <Text>JAZ, on the left. Messenger bag in her lap. Watching the road through the windshield over her father's shoulder. Her phone is in Hunter's hand.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a2baf377-0a5d-4c43-be0c-d741849cd1df">
      <Text>JAMIE, on the right. Hoodie pulled up. Bent over HUNTER'S DEAD PREPAID ANDROID— the cracked Samsung that Hunter has been nursing along through more than one administration, out of minutes, out of service. Jamie has it open. He is looking at the back of it with the focused attention of someone who has just identified a useful component in a system that is currently failing.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="87208ef7-87d8-4a72-8f02-cfd18ac4ad12">
      <Text>BEEEEEEEEEEP.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="2462e5ca-c5b5-463c-a268-1eb4d8a43196">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="819a32db-f2a9-4d6c-bf34-8e1b8b8dfcce">
      <Text>Hunter. We're fucking lost.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="6bcbbfff-1167-4606-877c-d60adae08364">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="f75e5b31-0127-4a11-8aac-6301251a1e3c">
      <Text>(into phone)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="86121f65-c1bb-49db-a6db-a3654fe88c62">
      <Text>One second, sir.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="909b6783-434a-476b-a323-1b8c38dc6235">
      <Text>(hand over phone, to Kevin)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="70cb78f9-6d35-462c-937b-5227113f936a">
      <Text>Kevin—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="73f46945-b5ac-4505-ba93-a62e7d4e57ae">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="63db3711-d5cb-41e4-a823-1afad8c19ccf">
      <Text>Tell him we're lost and to turn the alarms off. Tell him they're not helping.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="0ecf29a8-82e6-4bdf-a40e-9fbc28461691">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="48c676bd-1a65-4981-a44d-54ff71f59870">
      <Text>I—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="1ea426d4-3395-4627-9b2c-3bd36066529b">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="d92b269c-3d7a-462b-a719-31731d09d8c3">
      <Text>Give me the phone so I can navigate us out of here.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="453dc233-7dd5-4aa1-a1b8-78a4ac4b3ef9">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="6dc70fb1-63f2-4cd1-8132-585f18cf8b55">
      <Text>(through gritted teeth)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="c62d14be-58bc-4d7a-8f96-3c07f620575c">
      <Text>I cannot give you the phone. I am on the phone. If I get off this call this officer will log a violation and the court will issue a warrant for your immediate arrest. Both of your immediate arrests. That's what the alarms are. And-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="af04a139-2acc-4f6d-ab7f-a7ba7e4bbeb0">
      <Text>MONITORING OFFICER (O.S.)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="eae286ac-e78f-4cfa-90c2-1fa5132cf2ee">
      <Text>(more aggressive)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="5db8e778-5c05-4317-9310-c96c01796f66">
      <Text>Mr. Reid.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ec8cef71-35af-4086-9a85-723641089f01">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="94d02153-6d1e-4684-bc64-c4781433435e">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="f84f76ee-6bb0-41df-914e-6f6c6f18120f">
      <Text>(into phone)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="22f102f7-c2de-402f-ae6a-0c362d97854d">
      <Text>Yes sir, I'm right here. One more second, I need to confer with my client—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="c4b41de0-eab1-405e-b43c-f29b6672d15c">
      <Text>(to Kevin)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="3de2400e-76c5-4606-b40b-061e1fcf965a">
      <Text>The problem with your plan is that me being on this phone with Dennis Pruitt right now, is the only thing standing between this family and two separate revocation hearings, and two jail cells.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="09cd64b7-7118-47ab-82ee-7766cbbc2c25">
      <Text>(deep breath)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="0a50106d-8dc1-4004-b7ca-f605ae2d7dc0">
      <Text>And me getting disbarred and likely criminally charged in violation of Rule 1.2d- 8.4b- and clearly 3.4c- for handing you this FUCKING PHONE!</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="877a7589-d13e-4ce4-953c-045b262b27c0">
      <Text>The car drifts. A reflective road marker appears and disappears under the front bumper with a sound like a drumstick on a snare.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="71e1a9d2-e23f-481a-a670-378df5406c40">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="f91212ba-8d49-4754-9dc3-3576d6ed0301">
      <Text>HUNTER—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="aef87df0-ae46-410c-9365-174074b79746">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="23890f05-1f6a-4696-98c0-4b4bc647f2f2">
      <Text>I see it—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="f759dc10-d41c-48e3-a976-c5ed28100f7f">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="751bb841-a7d5-4510-a055-63cbad3eaf18">
      <Text>After you HIT it—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="7cc1cae0-93f6-414d-b233-499a376e552a">
      <Text>MONITORING OFFICER (O.S.)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="a4566ea5-33ea-4461-a72c-ffa1b43a313f">
      <Text>(sharp)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="d00270f2-794c-46a1-8301-8f295c53c30d">
      <Text>Mr. Reid. I need your precise location right now or I am logging this as a violation and we're done.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="fb0525a9-7ae4-4d72-8b8d-96d52b602336">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="38408916-21f4-49c1-bc38-23814df84d75">
      <Text>And from the back seat—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ee6d06c7-94bd-4748-b9b6-0159cc33bb8c">
      <Text>CHIME.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e16f1ec6-d95b-4792-a15e-53bc0249820d">
      <Text>Everyone's head turns.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7e8c5752-4fc6-4793-af20-03ab2467fc50">
      <Text>Hunter's previously dead prepaid Android. Which is now lit up. Back from the dead in Jamie’s hand. Actively receiving, in a cascades that shows no sign of stopping, message after message after message, the chime of each one arriving in rapid succession like a very specific kind of countdown.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7e4086f7-514a-4e9c-bcfb-41770b533ce9">
      <Text>CHIME. CHIME. CHIME.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="6d0f23e5-8675-45c7-921c-20794a74c5dc">
      <Text>JAMIE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="267b1cee-0789-4da9-a10d-0a48cd3b7228">
      <Text>(no preamble, the tone of someone reporting a weather update)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="c9067e1f-cfad-48e2-8db6-d97ab2015753">
      <Text>I pulled the </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">IMEI</Text>
      <Text> off it. I registered it as a replacement device on the family plan for moms phone. We have internet and GPS now.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="220c2958-4019-4866-827c-0e5fcc1659ca">
      <Text>He holds it up to Kevin to see. The screen bright in the dark car. The chimes keep coming.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e6662352-5b23-4101-9fbf-d3fa27ea566b">
      <Text>CHIME. CHIME.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b8840223-5236-46e1-b04f-3198893d2a24">
      <Text>Kevin turns all the way around in the passenger seat.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="29a5060a-8aba-4469-8637-7105056dd17d">
      <Text>CHIME</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0656ddb8-fa68-40ba-9f28-10f5462fef5b">
      <Text>He looks at the screen in his son’s hand.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f7832564-3d6b-4fd7-8898-d2d4e0336058">
      <Text>CHIME.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5862e032-e460-4ff2-a1fb-425b94f625f9">
      <Text>The messages are from Numbers. not Contacts— the contact names absent as the address book hasn’t had time or bandwidth to sync yet in rural Sussex county. They keep arriving, a backlog syncing all at once, weeks of incoming stacking in seconds.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="13fc83e2-48d1-46bb-984c-4936e0b79382">
      <Text>And there it is. A popped up texted picture, unmistakable-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="607696b8-c8c8-47eb-86c8-c2614e19ddbd">
      <Text>Chet Masters, Kevin’s fraternal brother, His Co-founder of MedAnalytics, the Material witness for the state on Kevin’s Martin Act charges and Janet’s conspiracy charges- Chet’s face is clear as day in the photo, as is his big hairy cock gripped firmly at camera, the message reads:</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="39202d24-06d6-4281-9df1-edd6c02f8b57">
      <Text>Miss you J. Can’t wait to stick this back in you tomorrow.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="aa783aff-cd95-45fc-9756-a18c47674f71">
      <Text>Kevin reflexively takes the phone from his son and pivots back around in his seat.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9819276d-5604-4001-b548-466a4dd3dfa1">
      <Text>Kevin's thumb moves. One slow scroll. Stops.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8bef2ef4-fc30-4439-9b9e-46895d8ba0ac">
      <Text>This is the longest thread. It’s still populating. The previous message reads:</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8bef2ef4-fc30-4439-9b9e-46895d8ba0ac">
      <Text>“Oh babe! I’m still sore from you draining me Tuesday.”</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8e9f92f2-bfa1-4f08-8cbb-e1b76b4f8934">
      <Text>The time stamp is 5 days ago.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0597e0b4-5638-43c6-851f-09d5728faad6">
      <Text>Kevin goes very still.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5f8a182a-b913-472d-89b4-8ef392b71bd4">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e8f6e1a6-3459-461d-bd34-325c1be4c262">
      <Text>In the center of the back seat, JANET's eyes move from the window to the back of Kevin's head. Her face drains. She does not move. She does not make a sound. She is very, very good at not making a sound.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="194cc3a8-c9ba-4910-922e-a4b673377a0e">
      <Text>Jaz is watching all of it, she can see the phone screen in the reflection in the passenger window glass. Her face gives nothing.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1e84071f-ccbe-4de3-8fab-14ac29262124">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="eb546eca-8701-45d5-9049-1a0af9fa0a90">
      <Text>Kevin closes the thread. Opens navigation. Types the address of the Playboy Resort, Great Gorge, New Jersey. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="eb546eca-8701-45d5-9049-1a0af9fa0a90">
      <Text>His hands are steady. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="eb546eca-8701-45d5-9049-1a0af9fa0a90">
      <Text>His jaw is working in the specific way of a man who is solving the operational problem in front of him because the operational problem in front of him is the only problem he is legally, physically, and logistically capable of addressing right now.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b861cf38-d88f-47ab-8086-9da8ce08ea7c">
      <Text>The blue line populates. There they are.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="00913a3d-5df2-4616-9b15-2c6b9d6cd67e">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="cfe6040b-0e00-4bb9-913d-418a9dd67e1e">
      <Text>(very even, to Hunter)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="456a36a8-77aa-4f5f-925a-5533f1a57a31">
      <Text>One mile. Stay on this road to the next right.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="5837e1ae-2978-49e7-80b8-3bfb48f6dee3">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="32677f5a-131a-4e1a-b985-09518631a24a">
      <Text>(to the monitoring officer)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="a6feb93c-1db2-45e1-b1de-3a1bc28dcd77">
      <Text>Sir, I can confirm we are one mile from the property, continuous approach. I'm going to ask you for a three-minute extension-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="73d4a31e-0658-4a9a-bb8f-ef8331dc105b">
      <Text>MONITORING OFFICER (O.S.)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="6f8a6841-b0ed-419b-a238-6dcedfd99f12">
      <Text>One mile. Three minutes. The system auto-flags at that point, there's nothing I can do after that.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="2d635b45-8f87-48bc-8d0e-8269af4c2778">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="4f4a3267-ebe8-4dbe-a197-3a517ae471ae">
      <Text>Three minutes. Thank you, sir. Very kind.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5181f062-9288-448d-a0ed-e5d966e699b2">
      <Text>The call disconnects.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f1e6b2d7-e04c-4f02-a94f-11d081d6612d">
      <Text>Kevin looks at the time. 11:35. He looks at the phone in his hand. He looks at the road.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4209cd86-895c-479f-9197-1cfde9fbfd87">
      <Text>He does not look at the back seat.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5ffd9d86-7143-4882-998e-854028fc2762">
      <Text>He turns. Hands the phone to Janet. Holds silent eye contact for a lingering second.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="15cbfe27-4bca-4c25-8f6e-9cd3bce243c6">
      <Text>Their fingers don't touch in the handoff. He faces forward. His jaw works. He says nothing. Because there is nothing he is legally permitted to say. Because his co-defendant is in the back seat. Because his attorney just got off the phone with the man who controls whether Kevin sleeps in a resort tonight or in a cell. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="15cbfe27-4bca-4c25-8f6e-9cd3bce243c6">
      <Text>Because his fourteen-year-old son and his daughter are also in the back seat. Because he is one mile from the only place he is allowed to be and the ankle monitor is still screaming and he found the turn.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ac89b50d-3d39-4e12-a9a9-52b5379ca1ef">
      <Text>He found the turn. That is what he can do right now. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ac89b50d-3d39-4e12-a9a9-52b5379ca1ef">
      <Text>He found the turn.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="022c30e9-82a7-4e2a-8da4-7323b4553a43">
      <Text>Janet takes the phone. Her thumb moves to the screen. She mutes it’s audio. She does not look at what's on it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="022c30e9-82a7-4e2a-8da4-7323b4553a43">
      <Text>She looks out the window at the dark New Jersey trees and holds the phone in her lap with both hands like it is something she needs to keep from moving.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c9268d77-6058-454a-9fa9-ab6386816f86">
      <Text>BLINK.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="752a4be5-b214-4da9-8ec1-b14eb3b26764">
      <Text>Muted now. The screen lighting up against her palm. Once. Twice. A third time.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9e4f4b5d-27b3-4fbf-bca5-8b08e877c83e">
      <Text>Jaz looks at the road.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8e7dd71e-bdda-4edd-a848-a3b77152a393">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="877054e8-7e61-4fa1-8a92-056a32500bf5">
      <Text>Nobody says anything.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f4965475-504e-4d37-87fe-8fa4af964983">
      <Text>BLINK.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7bb2ab8b-ce06-486e-a498-4e23d6aaa28c">
      <Text>Jaz looks at her mother. The mask firm, almost physical now more than metaphoric, except now, for everyone in this car for the first time, the mask is transparent. And no one can talk about it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="129b9d51-fb8a-4a40-a54a-33e26a4e7afa">
      <Text>Jaz reaches over, slowly grasping the phone in her mothers hands. Janet instinctively resists.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="b5152366-dc01-4e11-8836-4c493c2e394b">
      <Text>Jaz</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="27de8076-6f65-4e7e-9a1a-0b35b6d62586">
      <Text>You can’t legally have that.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="57097b2d-0727-4fdf-9662-06674f8267b5">
      <Text>Janet’s hand trembles, barely perceptibly.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="40f46a2c-9a65-40c5-aafd-a5587aec7311">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="a3253eb4-f692-4a07-8046-14b1e08fdcd9">
      <Text>(whispering, supportive)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="840399fa-bd0b-475e-b08c-5edcb7cc6a62">
      <Text>I got you- Mom.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e5cf31f2-b83f-4f57-96e2-b7e10059d566">
      <Text>And she takes it. powers it down, and slides it into her bag. Looks back out the window.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="92f3dff9-383d-4087-bbe9-d9a538c58712">
      <Text>The road straightens. The tree line thins. And then—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0b01669a-0a59-48ce-abf7-6de0d2d81c4d">
      <Text>The engine hiccups.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1eff21ec-8ce8-4672-8145-fa951ed42d08">
      <Text>A single, small, unmistakable mechanical interruption in the rhythm of the drive. Everyone in the car feels it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="4d3bc947-5edd-4587-acda-bec54e15d35a">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="70694032-a47a-44cc-965c-8b58f5b23498">
      <Text>Don't.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="04847347-b82b-48df-ae34-a36b72b1816f">
      <Text>Another hiccup. Longer.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="990c214f-043c-4df5-9034-ff14d29a28c6">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="f6be6788-5aed-4770-8abb-70b95ef7dbc6">
      <Text>Don't you do it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="cb3f0fd4-2144-4aef-9be0-006e7bf2b500">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="0f34e6ef-07d8-47ca-a986-8387a0c8f79c">
      <Text>What was—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="3dc8c8a6-c424-4d53-8fa6-688386eb1ae2">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="99885014-05e0-42e3-a032-907fe5f5f168">
      <Text>It's fine. The car is fine.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="cc4ac127-08a9-4dd3-b62d-6675693ad919">
      <Text>The engine hiccups again. And again. The rhythm breaking apart under them like ice in April.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="08904f05-dc74-4dc4-8c67-8ae37e8f6349">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="20ac92e1-f36c-44e7-8211-f09640449d29">
      <Text>(to the car, with genuine feeling)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="0e1e652d-38b7-4f67-8c00-9c150f21ad0b">
      <Text>Come ON.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="672bf2f4-fd06-4ef6-ac2d-9046147ad9b7">
      <Text>The engine gives one long, shuddering, dignified groan.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="cc4fe73a-e1db-4c14-9f0e-a04556452b43">
      <Text>And stops.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="dacc1260-782a-4139-94f7-3c0712cef724">
      <Text>No grinding. No drama. Just— silence where there was sound. The power steering goes heavy in Hunter's hands. The headlights dim on battery. The car rolls on its own momentum, slower and slower, gravel crunching, and coasts to a stop at the shoulder.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0b159d58-65d3-4064-b089-754edc75f8b2">
      <Text>Silence. Other than—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5f20651a-e30a-4120-9e9d-4a6cfa73761d">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="61c8d34c-82dc-477f-a079-2a3c40a848f8">
      <Text>Hunter stares at the wheel. At the dark road. At the phone.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ebc9924a-1f7b-4f6a-8bfc-e22f6fce8c7c">
      <Text>A beat.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5d77563c-5574-4d50-ae96-0530047621b8">
      <Text>He opens his door.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="af392b92-a2ec-4138-840c-70c9a2354c1d">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="a3979ae5-beab-4980-a20c-45128158cf15">
      <Text>Run.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5b31a5b5-9399-473b-8abb-f478c255d033">
      <Text>Kevin gets out. Ankle monitors going </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text> into the dark New Jersey night, into the tree-lined two-lane road with nothing visible in any direction except the distant smear of what might be a sign just ahead in the headlights.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5db6321a-2f30-42c5-89ba-5f5f2b95c276">
      <Text>Hunter runs, brown bag in hand. There was never a version of this evening where Hunter left that bottle in a diner booth.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ec38986a-44f3-42be-a6c3-cf329b8b3c82">
      <Text>JANET. Lululemon and Hunter's jacket and bare determination. Scrambles out. She runs. The monitor on her ankle screaming into the dark alongside Kevin's like a duet nobody asked for.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b4fde09b-8903-411d-bf20-d0d509dbcbf8">
      <Text>JAMIE. Hoodie. He runs.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="089476bd-d882-45d5-bf7e-4419f596317c">
      <Text>JAZ. Messenger bag across her hip, combat boots on rural New Jersey asphalt at midnight.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9d08b9b2-80eb-436f-b588-a0df60c5b2e3">
      <Text>She walks. Lights a smoke form her bag.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e62be55c-b931-410f-8815-936f0a971974">
      <Text>The sign materializes in the dark ahead. Kevin sees it first.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="40bf8413-12dd-4d6b-afad-a0623e456d2e">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="ed933357-d212-4a5f-bb09-bb6bf937910c">
      <Text>(running, pointing)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="757cbea6-db86-4085-a514-8454b14b4cc6">
      <Text>THERE.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d3defa8c-e58a-4368-875b-8b81940c8362">
      <Text>A sign. Old, weathered, but legible in the way that only hope can make them:</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b5e821d8-8ab8-441a-9e74-164c4416d2f4">
      <Text>PLAYBOY RESORT HOTEL</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8c641c81-849b-419c-b845-d43b19120d16">
      <Text>GREAT GORGE, NEW JERSEY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d3f50511-eccb-4844-af89-f4dc608bd810">
      <Text>PRIVATE DRIVE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9ae44ade-a205-4110-bf4f-c2d112746e40">
      <Text>They turn off the road onto it at full sprint.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="bc9f8919-a55b-44cf-a230-e66d494fc43e">
      <Text>The driveway is cracked asphalt and twenty years of neglect and it does not care about any of that right now. They run down it, the two ankle monitors carrying through the dark in unison, and then—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="29ee186c-f94c-44f0-9533-bd8d8a61787e">
      <Text>Kevin stops running.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="54b7d6db-7662-447d-b0b5-d0e395cf767a">
      <Text>He's on the property. He knows it the way you know it when the ground changes under you.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="c8bd5ce6-074e-47ba-a4da-a261ba17c0a5">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="5c70df7a-6d58-4db4-8b97-5c9579634145">
      <Text>(panting, to Hunter)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="9aadc581-f3b5-4a61-a273-22bb640a153e">
      <Text>We're on property. We're on— what the fuck— we're on property—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="fbb71628-8e5b-40c2-960c-68b82cdb39ef">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>. </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">BEEEEEEEEEEP</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5b572aa5-75b8-4aa9-a456-9d5c461b1676">
      <Text>Hunter holds up the phone.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="43a5301d-ce73-4e6e-be7c-fb4139d7e2b2">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="ade21f88-6144-48cd-acd2-b06d5c439d44">
      <Text>Fifteen seconds.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="98d1eabd-ecda-4777-a66b-570572535e39">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="70213db8-53d5-4e47-aa9a-9c50a3c25620">
      <Text>What?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="dc6b3b9a-a59d-445c-b383-05fa266027c5">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="21f7721b-86da-43ae-9e34-3a4a70e8f7fc">
      <Text>Fifteen.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="ef724d75-d522-4543-a2f9-157496d06890">
      <Text>(watching the screen)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="5ba63274-af40-4eb7-ad1b-1d4790b6ea7b">
      <Text>Ten.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="faadef57-55d4-407e-8a06-49219e0c5cff">
      <Text>The ankle monitors BEEP.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="08d9eb11-c2c9-42bf-ac29-ebb22a7f619f">
      <Text>BEEP.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="64dbff74-bd5e-4e3e-a955-c5655190d4f9">
      <Text>BEEP.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b461ffff-0a92-40d9-b7b4-5e36fcc5b028">
      <Text>BEEP.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8f46fdb0-1f83-4336-a585-6ac583f70c8f">
      <Text>And then—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="508317de-4262-437e-aa51-4a14f93d60c1">
      <Text>Silence.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2ee9fd75-15ad-4f98-a8ce-80b164760502">
      <Text>Merciful, complete, total silence, broken only by four people breathing hard on a private driveway in rural New Jersey in the dark. Both monitor lights flicker from red to solid green in the same instant. Two small green pulses blinking in the dark like a pair of eyes.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8b0c6f0d-9ea5-474d-8413-edce98a82cbb">
      <Text>Kevin straightens. Points at his ankle. Looks at the others. Hunter looks at Kevin.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6c5cc0e5-65dd-4b09-9ee6-2f28fdb16db2">
      <Text>They erupt.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ee3fd3e4-0fd4-4b1d-852c-802d295ed2d1">
      <Text>Loudly. Not elegantly. But completely— Hunter pumping the paper bag in the air, Kevin with two fists up like he's just closed something, Jamie doing a small precise fist pump that contains all the same emotion at one-tenth the amplitude. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ee3fd3e4-0fd4-4b1d-852c-802d295ed2d1">
      <Text>Janet laughs— really laughs, the unpracticed kind, the kind that has been waiting to get out since a Lululemon outfit and a pair of handcuffs on a sidewalk this morning—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="933a7a8d-37d5-4257-923e-2ca24fde2c6a">
      <Text>Ten seconds of pure uncomplicated family chaos. Ten seconds that have been a long time coming.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e3f556c8-051e-46db-be0d-7fee08354a95">
      <Text>Jaz walks up. Clapping like they just won the big game.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="82ed4c0f-93a8-471a-a294-178729ea9b2d">
      <Text>And then—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e270de94-3e47-4bc8-9df3-bc4ef29a5620">
      <Text>Something HOWLS from the tree line.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3f2fae5b-ef3a-4025-bbf5-45e2cfbade9a">
      <Text>Deep. Close. Not a dog. Something that lives here, that has always lived here, that does not particularly care about GPS monitoring or bail conditions or the events of the last twenty-four hours.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="af41c7c3-57ad-4c45-9076-bb525c17333c">
      <Text>The celebration stops.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="30c85ec5-f82e-45c5-8acf-56639d11a1b7">
      <Text>Five people stand on a cracked private driveway in the dark and look at the tree line.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="9239bc38-4778-4c0b-97d5-fefca2690b29">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="ad697855-9fda-4f38-abbe-8a8f429975fa">
      <Text>(very quietly)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="7e7284a3-fc5f-42b8-a2b8-1c316f0cfcb9">
      <Text>What was that.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c48a1faa-a71f-48f3-b996-9dcf812a9c27">
      <Text>Nobody answers.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5eb0ce99-513f-4741-8446-c8dd4aaa6d09">
      <Text>The trees are very dark and very close.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="72931b5f-8347-4b8a-b66f-b0fd56de7356">
      <Text>Jaz takes a long drag on her cigarette. She extracts her pack of smokes, offers it to Hunter as an exchange. The Jameson slides from Hunter's paper bag.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="72931b5f-8347-4b8a-b66f-b0fd56de7356">
      <Text>She takes a pull, hands it back by the neck. He takes it without question. Tips it back. A long, grateful pull. Wipes his mouth. She tosses him her pack.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="38e851c7-46b3-4573-9e83-b4188edea01c">
      <Text>Then she looks up.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="87e62bab-f7e8-499b-8106-6fd4fd42eb50">
      <Text>Above them, through the gap in the tree canopy where the driveway cuts through— stars. A lot of them. Sussex County is not known for much, but light pollution it has handled. The stars are thick and real.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="90e2544f-888c-47f4-9a62-cbc81a0600a1">
      <Text>And against them: an absence. A shape. Enormous. Angular. A darkness so solid and so large it blots out a significant portion of the sky. The outline of an eight story roofline against the night.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="65b0b5b9-2373-4472-9630-56b4fa25e157">
      <Text>The Playboy Resort, Great Gorge, New Jersey.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6819d02d-6478-4116-81f0-ad69eef59fec">
      <Text>Jaz looks at it. The sheer volume of dark it occupies. Not a single detail visible from here— just the fact of it. Enormous and waiting and completely, entirely hers.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c6278df0-72f1-4fd2-96cd-c5f74e85e497">
      <Text>She takes one more pull of the cigarette.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="46d1d6b1-256b-4227-9a4a-53e9016aa594">
      <Text>Turns.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a6da8956-5c14-4a35-8a51-55c723cbfe93">
      <Text>And walks. Down the long private driveway, toward her new possession, without looking back.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e1b98d60-4b12-4154-afff-fb6741927307">
      <Text>One beat. Then another.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d675ee4d-f640-48a4-b6db-2de3bb5fec3a">
      <Text>Kevin watches her go. The Phoenix he doesn't know.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="24a6ccf5-eb74-4e7f-b3f9-d070baf96967">
      <Text>In his peripheral vision: Janet. Standing in the dark. The monitor on her ankle blinking green. Hunter's jacket around her shoulders.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4a8ed0ee-d47a-4f44-8f0b-01622ede8fc5">
      <Text>She is not looking at him. She is looking at the building.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="41526db8-cc9e-4181-be15-f34a832aba5a">
      <Text>He wants to say something. There is nothing he is allowed to say. He doesn't know yet what half of it means. He knows enough.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="12f92464-a55b-4a7d-9c43-2d35fc9bc73a">
      <Text>He starts walking.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="0b19a5c1-6ad5-4033-8751-81d33909677f">
      <SceneProperties Length="3 3/8" Page="14" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="DIANA">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="PRIYA">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. MANHATTAN DA'S OFFICE - DIANA'S OFFICE - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c3529340-81e2-499c-8380-607939695d2b">
      <Text>The building has that specific late-night texture. The custodial hum. The particular quality of quiet that only exists in offices where the absence of people makes the presence of the work louder. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c3529340-81e2-499c-8380-607939695d2b">
      <Text>ADA DIANA LIANG's office: Framed commendations on the wall, hung with the precision of someone who understands that visible achievement and personal pride are two different administrative categories. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c3529340-81e2-499c-8380-607939695d2b">
      <Text>A desk that is organized— not for aesthetics, but for retrieval speed. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c3529340-81e2-499c-8380-607939695d2b">
      <Text>Her monitor casts everything in the cool blue of scanned documents. The McCort case file. Specifically: the MedAnalytic transaction timeline. Specifically: a chain of internal communications she has been reading, in one form or another, for six hours. She reads the same page she read ninety minutes ago. And before that. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="daf9becf-1a03-437f-b9c0-98d11da4fe4b">
      <Text>On the corner of her desk: a photograph. Framed. Four by six. Sara is turned toward the camera in the way of someone who just noticed it, mid-laugh, a small explosion of unguarded warmth that photographs are not supposed to catch but sometimes do. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="daf9becf-1a03-437f-b9c0-98d11da4fe4b">
      <Text>Next to Sara, pressed against Sara's left ankle with the specific determination of a creature who believes personal space is a human failing, a </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">Shih</Text>
      <Text> </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">Tzu</Text>
      <Text> of such extravagant puffiness that he appears to have opinions about it. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="daf9becf-1a03-437f-b9c0-98d11da4fe4b">
      <Text>Next to it is a another frame, Diana and Sara and Henri, on a roof deck somewhere in better weather, looking like the kind of photograph that ends up in frames. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c3529340-81e2-499c-8380-607939695d2b">
      <Text>Diana's phone is face-up on the desk.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="72847141-ee80-420e-abb7-7a32da8074d3">
      <Text>SARA: (TEXT) are you still coming tonight</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8a253e70-6b7e-465f-bd01-7e2d9f609dd6">
      <Text>SARA: (TEXT) just to be clear Henri has been sitting by the door for an hour</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6bee5491-4c79-464b-8a3b-5103e0f23e4a">
      <Text>SARA: (TEXT) i'm going to tell him you're stuck at work as usual</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d604e3b3-24b0-48d6-839b-7b277768bf9c">
      <Text>SARA: (TEXT) he does not believe me</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e691a1f7-12c9-4956-bb5e-44fe76f3d3bb">
      <Text>SARA: (TEXT) you are the one that threw a fit about having the little stinker with you tonight</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e0944cf1-ecaf-45a6-a143-85d6cd9fd308">
      <Text>SARA: (TEXT)...</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2ca92dca-9205-409e-9b79-28a45d259e34">
      <Text>Diana reads them. She does not respond to them. She reads them the way she reads documents she has not decided what to do with yet: completely, without flinching, and then she puts them down. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2ca92dca-9205-409e-9b79-28a45d259e34">
      <Text>She goes back to the McCort timeline. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2ca92dca-9205-409e-9b79-28a45d259e34">
      <Text>Footsteps in the hall.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2ca92dca-9205-409e-9b79-28a45d259e34">
      <Text>PRIYA </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">SOOD</Text>
      <Text> appears in the doorway, coat on, bag over her shoulder, the look of someone who has remembered what an outside is.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="58a1a07c-e7b8-470c-a073-9f25c295ace6">
      <Text>PRIYA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="40564547-207d-4014-bbec-a4e759d2dc14">
      <Text>Di. It is eleven-forty eight.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="884ee2cc-d46a-4adf-a872-9741629acc77">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="c22ed370-18d8-44be-b0d5-cfc829349ca1">
      <Text>(not looking up)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="50973f65-678c-4747-b8a7-48a2549aebd2">
      <Text>I know what time it is.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="66d04471-9438-4dfe-89a9-c0ea91ca65ed">
      <Text>PRIYA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="06e372ba-17ea-45e9-b4c4-e702dd32bbe4">
      <Text>The last Metro-North out of Grand Central that gets me to </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">Dobbs</Text>
      <Text> Ferry before this becomes a different kind of problem left three minutes ago. So that's solved.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="ea98e9ad-acfd-416d-84f5-42aaa07510a0">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="799a51ae-c5bc-4221-96c0-37c950152754">
      <Text>There's a twelve-ten.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="1cfcd6d9-1a67-4220-8f2a-ddb0bbd293ec">
      <Text>PRIYA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="c4655cd3-db61-4e7a-ba12-c7d7e25de701">
      <Text>No.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="29a97090-191c-436b-a16e-f90d4a099d07">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="9af37394-a965-4f4c-910a-7ba226c11e1f">
      <Text>There's a twelve-ten, it connects at—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="421b51c0-a83c-449b-a0e2-a13300f3c18b">
      <Text>PRIYA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="9540d71b-725b-480c-b21a-bcc159fde4e3">
      <Text>There is not a twelve-ten that a human person with a deposition at seven-thirty AM should be on. I know there's a twelve-ten. The twelve-ten is a ghost train. The twelve-ten is for people who have already given up.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="2ea68ff7-3e8a-48f3-bb76-066fb8b2cd3e">
      <Text>(beat)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="d939e07f-bf5e-40c6-bd50-f2dc04e52b67">
      <Text>Can I crash on your and Sara's couch?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="fa1af039-7380-4555-a2e4-884d6566c74d">
      <Text>A small pause. Barely measurable. The kind that is only detectable to someone who is paying close attention, which Priya is not.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="5315ccd6-04a7-4b12-b3ea-9f14dfef4768">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="000d8f6b-49d2-4707-a617-9fc357e5531b">
      <Text>(very even)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="4ba6645d-a2a0-427b-93bc-b2a8fa0b2661">
      <Text>It's just Sara's couch. As of yesterday.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3be2ecf2-3c85-49e8-8c2b-9021705a544c">
      <Text>Priya stares at her.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="cc428ac1-aca2-41f4-a327-97b6f7b8a84d">
      <Text>PRIYA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="5d3f6836-a425-4a2e-8dc1-22db2be1c862">
      <Text>Oh.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="fc9be1a7-f147-4dba-8d04-b9f9893193a8">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="a13830d0-f3cb-4e05-b17c-f50aa49ef624">
      <Text>Yes.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="9b108ada-e0bc-4d54-b386-75893361bbb1">
      <Text>PRIYA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="c69d0add-b992-4633-ab1b-0b9148c29dc7">
      <Text>Diana—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="f47e54c3-a8b3-4d82-a9b5-b316257567a8">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="adbe454a-5ad2-4609-963c-8249865e8497">
      <Text>You should probably get the twelve-ten.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2527e008-6973-490e-b7f7-da4415f07a40">
      <Text>Priya gets the unspoken message that she just doesn't want to talk about it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="71700d40-2327-4a29-a8a7-bd3ce16a93a0">
      <Text>PRIYA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="51b9396c-0c52-4a17-a1db-f2c0e76cbd8d">
      <Text>(carefully)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="d3caf15a-7a56-490f-9755-1ae1132ee0c6">
      <Text>Okay. I'm going to get a hotel. And I'm going to text you tomorrow.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="0c07c947-1966-4d1e-b526-ee8a508ccf6f">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="24d94868-25ea-4328-8723-e4a271a98c6e">
      <Text>You don't need to—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="c2a1d37e-b41c-45f1-8866-57ecbe300c5a">
      <Text>PRIYA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="d74451af-004b-4bdb-9813-fb180180fa97">
      <Text>I'm going to text you tomorrow.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="b6ce8f4a-7e8e-40ec-9cf9-0f9a12674d12">
      <Text>(moving)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="d5eb7b95-a358-4bc7-8a43-d242c4311051">
      <Text>Go home, Di. The perp will still be guilty in the morning.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2898f236-90a2-4d26-b6a8-700e26689f9c">
      <Text>She is already in the hall. Diana is already back on the page.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="98841fd5-f020-4d55-9a8f-b1bdc995d530">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="b1c7656a-8e52-4ea5-9637-9aa8c54e3ba3">
      <Text>(without looking up)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="b64bb411-f401-45ea-b780-c951011fb2a7">
      <Text>Hey.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ebf61629-1c9b-4374-95ae-0fb7390ca41a">
      <Text>Priya stops.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="1b956755-5505-4d58-be50-d2bd23d2ed22">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="7c326055-3076-47d1-ab4e-1b114794926a">
      <Text>Hunter Reid. Criminal defense, private practice, sole practice. Columbia Law, graduated—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="56b9c9b9-4804-48ab-a68d-703c9a4d6448">
      <Text>(she's already looked it up.)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="435963a6-4601-4558-8c1f-c51585381db0">
      <Text>—2015. Three years ahead of us. Does that name mean anything to you?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="42ff965c-b73d-49c4-b950-f280409c2b9e">
      <Text>Priya leans back into the doorway.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="ebd864e1-db79-4f0f-a229-e5e98ebe7d0c">
      <Text>PRIYA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="7fa10ee2-9782-48d3-b0dc-eba2caccc8cc">
      <Text>Hunter Reid. Nope.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="65632378-a07f-484a-af60-a3fd91f09c44">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="d7cff8b7-5237-4933-ac04-ef75d01a22d2">
      <Text>This is who Kevin McCort is putting his entire defense in the hands of.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="c14abdd6-8533-437f-8b53-fe5408293259">
      <Text>PRIYA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="8f227326-0673-4efa-a994-3f1712452885">
      <Text>Is he any good?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="f04b854e-6643-4d04-a4e5-c385348549d1">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="8ae0a34e-dca0-471f-9fce-1d86f82846e5">
      <Text>(a very specific pause)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="e7e7df58-7602-434e-bc6b-4208a4d818c3">
      <Text>No.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="7ce9c9d6-8e5a-44fc-b269-721bd9de46c3">
      <SceneProperties Length="2 2/8" Page="17" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="TANNER">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>EXT. MURRAY HILL - TANNER'S BUILDING - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="33ed610e-deb0-4586-99ea-99922ca4addf">
      <Text>An Uber Black Escalade idles at the curb with the quiet confidence of a vehicle that has no idea what it just transported.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d308b5f6-b77b-4643-a931-63a389170f0c">
      <Text>The door opens.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8073704d-dd37-46dc-914a-62129611d5fa">
      <Text>TANNER </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">SONNEFELD</Text>
      <Text> emerges.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="022e75a6-9067-4f4d-8460-842e7a69535d">
      <Text>In an I LOVE NEW YORK zip-up hoodie, XXL, the kind sold from a folding table on a midtown sidewalk to tourists who left their own jackets somewhere and needed to not be cold right now. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="022e75a6-9067-4f4d-8460-842e7a69535d">
      <Text>The price tag is still attached. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="022e75a6-9067-4f4d-8460-842e7a69535d">
      <Text>It hangs over a hospital gown that stops approximately mid-thigh. His feet are in dress socks. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="022e75a6-9067-4f4d-8460-842e7a69535d">
      <Text>His right hand is still wrapped in hospital gauze completely soaked through at this point and has gone the specific brownish-red of a bandage that needed changing several hours ago. That pinky finger. Still gone.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="022e75a6-9067-4f4d-8460-842e7a69535d">
      <Text>He is holding his phone to his ear with his left hand like it is the one structural element keeping his entire architecture upright.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="0e1472d1-b901-41b4-8023-e0a1d6a7c9cb">
      <Text>TANNER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="af6321e7-b768-40ac-a53d-f3d952e29764">
      <Text>(into phone)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="e4988fda-d230-4329-a7ec-0896c5c5b4c6">
      <Text>No— Jimmy, don't be like that. Bro, you know I can fix this.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="58d5a7f0-6ab6-4f9f-bfab-57aa22da9891">
      <Text>(listening)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="9fc11f2a-467d-4e30-9074-90456fbeb4eb">
      <Text>Bro— sorry, no more Bro-s- I know. I know- I'm not your brother. But Jimmy, I'm still your boy.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="e564394d-6e8f-4cfc-8240-ec7dba8b42fb">
      <Text>(listening)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="9fc11f2a-467d-4e30-9074-90456fbeb4eb">
      <Text>No, I can't find her. I looked everywhere.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="f7d0208e-1a36-4812-b247-ddc199f8370e">
      <Text>(listening)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="9fc11f2a-467d-4e30-9074-90456fbeb4eb">
      <Text>Yes. I asked around. Nobody knows her real name.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="26dc70e0-bf97-4884-b603-850064a722ba">
      <Text>He is walking toward the building entrance with the posture of a man who has decided that posturing is load-bearing right now. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="26dc70e0-bf97-4884-b603-850064a722ba">
      <Text>CLARENCE, the doorman, is at his post inside the glass door. Clarence sees Tanner coming. Clarence does the math. Clarence takes a significant step to the left.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2542b243-ee36-476d-a469-899fa4552eb5">
      <Text>Tanner pushes through the door.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ea1e2354-5fd4-4f7b-9cd9-dd74a90ed923">
      <Text>He mock-jabs with his left hand. Clarence flinches with his entire body.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="e45378d8-5599-428f-88ff-c3e5e79ea00c">
      <Text>TANNER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="aa8d261a-f77f-4199-ac63-b900b9af7005">
      <Text>(to Clarence)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="12f5857f-e177-42ec-b504-1508e0915afb">
      <Text>Pussy.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="44daa57c-a97b-46db-a764-c9694de19e8e">
      <Text>(back into the phone, instantly)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="f1130016-5ea8-4a1e-b13f-ceecda04d52b">
      <Text>No! Jimmy— not you— you know you're my— oh. Right.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="6e3099bd-fe5a-4db7-810f-6766b85776aa">
      <Text>(a specific pause)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="f1130016-5ea8-4a1e-b13f-ceecda04d52b">
      <Text>I'm sorry, Jimmy.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="845fa32d-32e3-4097-a33f-1bea50d4b0b6">
      <Text>He moves through the lobby. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="845fa32d-32e3-4097-a33f-1bea50d4b0b6">
      <Text>A LITTLE OLD CHINESE WOMAN is waiting for the elevator with a Yorkie that has been groomed within an inch of its life and is wearing a plaid vest. The woman clocks Tanner— </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="debd8dd2-05c0-4872-8906-d2bcabc23317">
      <Text>The Yorkie takes one look and retreats behind her ankles.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="73ca2f13-7f01-4629-a679-b966a13fe090">
      <Text>Tanner stabs the elevator button.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="71b43cdc-761f-4c85-9c3f-90a018206924">
      <Text>TANNER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="a1110a8d-c7ef-4a20-aab0-e3a6f5f445af">
      <Text>(into phone)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="1565c61b-76a1-43d9-b4fe-56078b01cc8d">
      <Text>Can't the firm just tell you her name? They would've needed it to register the transfer — you can't do the deed without—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="d3f31975-5c21-4ea5-9440-b954ca28af94">
      <Text>(listening)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="bd7403e9-d3bc-4f46-bd4b-0cf8dd506ffe">
      <Text>Yeah. Yeah, obviously. No, I don't want them coming down on you, Jimmy, that's the last thing—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="1d88b09b-e2c6-4809-a248-a4fd546993d3">
      <Text>(listening)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="bb28a3a9-991a-403b-8ac4-8974e269dfed">
      <Text>Yeah, I'm just getting home now. I've been out all day. Looking.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5681db57-c912-4ff4-b65f-e63d49f6002a">
      <Text>The elevator arrives. Tanner steps in. The little old woman and the Yorkie do not step in. A mutual and unspoken agreement.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="93578e25-0707-4267-8456-026ee93d6ea3">
      <Text>TANNER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="76aa6374-9e41-45f9-8f92-4b1de8f5d20b">
      <Text>I'm going up to Sussex County first thing. The county recorder's office, I'll be there when they open the doors and pull the docs. Whoever she registered it under, it's going to be in the record.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="5a7d4e00-3a91-4c95-8aa3-2d02ef462635">
      <Text>(listening)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="7e6c6151-d588-4436-9c1a-44e4c970fb4a">
      <Text>Yes. Yes, Jimmy, I'll call you the second I have it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="436e5cdd-2402-499a-b733-ad5c8b70576b">
      <Text>(listening)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="0a4bece5-6389-4043-b13e-fe4469fae2d6">
      <Text>And your name will never come up. That's what you've got me for, remember?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="8a951229-d0b1-4448-a3db-744610cddb32">
      <Text>(listening)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="407575dd-51a1-4a03-a6da-e0dcdd0b8275">
      <Text>Of course Bro-.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="f44504e1-30dd-4747-8a3b-92469f93cee2">
      <Text>(one more beat)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="c0ef5664-e662-40d2-9af7-b1aab3a9c75f">
      <Text>Oh— right. Sorry, Jimmy.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f2329e57-af27-4949-8d46-30c39d3e74e5">
      <Text>The elevator doors close.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="1e523f8e-e85a-406f-aafe-ad9e3f19f1ad">
      <SceneProperties Length="5 3/8" Page="19" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="HUNTER">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAMIE">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JANET">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAZ">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="KEVIN">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>EXT. PLAYBOY RESORT, GREAT GORGE - POOL DECK - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e147d340-1f19-4e09-bb4b-983535326974">
      <Text>Filling the frame completely, edge to edge, the way vacation photographs from a long gone era were composed— with the confidence that this image would last forever.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e5eb677a-043e-4d85-b615-3aea0cd49af1">
      <Text>The pool is an impossible blue. The specific, chlorinated, art-directed blue of a resort water. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e5eb677a-043e-4d85-b615-3aea0cd49af1">
      <Text>Lounge chairs in perfect rows, occupied by people who are posed doing perfect lounge chair things— tan, unhurried, architecturally relaxed in the way of a generation. The women in one-pieces that are somehow more suggestive than anything that came in the decades after. The men with mustaches that arrived with complete sincerity. Hair everywhere.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="59b004ae-cf89-4aab-aac3-11ffb3726b3e">
      <Text>Beyond them: the building. The grand glass wall, floor to ceiling, framed in beige river rock the color of something geological, something that predates the resort by several hundred million years and is merely tolerating its current decorative assignment. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="59b004ae-cf89-4aab-aac3-11ffb3726b3e">
      <Text>Through the glass: the restaurant. Full. Warmth that only exists when every table is occupied and no one is looking at a phone.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3b296460-f517-484b-bf4b-ab630024f502">
      <Text>This photograph is a perfect scene. The photograph is exactly what the Playboy Resort, Great Gorge, New Jersey was supposed to be forever.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="94f0935d-62fa-4847-a373-26edd74e4f72">
      <Text>A thin beam of light moves across it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="91c44bc6-e01f-439b-99c1-10c239b6ff3f">
      <Text>An iPhone flashlight. Held by a human hand. Illuminating the photograph from below, traveling slowly upward, the way you read something you want to understand completely before you respond to it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="429687db-564a-4e3d-9e80-9b9a67a4f720">
      <Text>The beam holds on the restaurant. On the people in it. On the river rock. On the pool.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1b3e7f27-d9b6-474c-b41b-ca64948729a3">
      <Text>Then the hand lowers.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c7f09970-b3fa-457d-9031-2d3a50c2f122">
      <Text>The photograph drifts down out of frame.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="97bc07e3-6025-4aa6-81f8-addf5c3f0994">
      <Text>And beneath it—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="347cfd4a-95eb-48c1-b546-6888015d4a7b">
      <Text>The same shot.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="03d33b50-8d03-4848-845d-a92aff55cf61">
      <Text>Identical framing. Same angle, same geometry, same compositional logic. We have found the exact position the resort photographer stood in, sometime in 1975 or 1977 or 1979, and has not moved an inch.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="153a2524-9c06-4c48-ba16-2d724ab6f90c">
      <Text>It is 12:10 AM.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e60ec931-7364-433c-b193-791c0b37ea0a">
      <Text>The iPhone beam hits the windows first. The reflection comes back harsh and immediate— a single white pinpoint bouncing off glass that has accumulated a decade's worth of particulate matter, organic film, the specific patina of a surface that has been rained on and dried and rained on again without anyone paying attention.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="fe69f2da-88dd-4037-85fb-4799e9ff1b57">
      <Text>The pool itself is green. Algae in layers. Decades of falling leaves composted into a substrate. Weeds that have rooted through the pool deck coping and grown down into the water and up through it and sideways along it, establishing a quiet, thorough, completely indifferent ecosystem.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d11d2d1d-7e69-4097-bf8b-ee1e3510f9ff">
      <Text>The lounge chairs are in there. Visible just beneath the surface in the iPhone beam-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>white aluminum frames gone gray, cushions long since dissolved into the biology of the pool, the chairs themselves resting at the angles they landed when the water found them or the years pushed them in. A row of them, still. Patient. Doing their best.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="34416a94-5672-4da5-bf46-e98126f45e56">
      <Text>The beam travels to the building.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6b2cba47-2f98-4120-8ba1-af43e384f33f">
      <Text>The river rock is still there. Immovable. It was always going to outlast everything around it and it has.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ee43d81c-c3c6-4548-9551-f801d05166fb">
      <Text>The hand-stained pre-cut Oregon pine— selected from a mill catalog by someone who cared, who specified the grade and the stain and the application, who signed off on this material specifically because of how it would look against the river rock— </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ee43d81c-c3c6-4548-9551-f801d05166fb">
      <Text>It's been losing a thirty-year argument with weather and gravity and the absence of anyone to intervene. Boards warped outward at the ends. Sections pulled away from the rock entirely, leaving the raw fastening hardware exposed in the beam. In one section along the far wall the pine is simply gone, and the river rock stands alone, unbothered, precisely as it was.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f7ae1915-87bf-424a-bf00-9ef5673048a9">
      <Text>The copper accent that originally traced every elegant line now pulled like taffy.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="343474cc-daf7-4e6c-9c75-e61cf697f3e9">
      <Text>The double glass doors: gone. What replaced them at some point — years ago, by someone with plywood and approximate measurements and a pragmatic relationship to aesthetics — are two sections of </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">OSB</Text>
      <Text> board, rough-cut.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="37e66829-aea3-46da-8f4c-e99a68cd02b9">
      <Text>The beam holds on the doors for a moment.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="96519724-d64b-4ce2-84a4-c347fa0c0371">
      <Text>Same shot. Same angle.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0d67d742-15bb-4a57-9f70-18fc87482976">
      <Text>Different universe.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Shot" id="be86cad6-48d0-4758-9ce0-7e1ed6fac159">
      <Text>REVERSE:</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c09a9921-5ef6-4ea2-8b59-eecc84a389dd">
      <Text>KEVIN is holding the pamphlet up. He has found the exact position the photograph was taken from and he is aligning the image in the pamphlet with what is in front of him with the focused, slightly desperate concentration of a man who believes that if he can get the geometry right something else might follow.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="08026f53-256e-4545-8f59-c090e6578059">
      <Text>It is not following.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="fb8b609a-b1b1-4d3c-b13e-95afe6cb790a">
      <Text>The pamphlet photograph and the building in front of him occupy the same coordinates and share no other qualities. He holds it up. He adjusts. He holds it up again.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f9a7710d-e33e-4186-b6ed-005582f67259">
      <Text>JAZ is standing beside him with her phone flashlight on. Behind her face is doing a similar amount of calculations, but from a totally different perspective and angle. Intrigued. Curious. The look of someone who has clocked something worth keeping. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="226dcfdc-2c6a-428c-a9ba-96db4951d2d9">
      <Text>She and Kevin exchange a look, a game of chicken over who is going to speak first.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="698c4bac-440f-4588-88e6-df3e29f3a0ce">
      <Text>She is not flinching.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0bb6d30d-ae6b-4f7f-b96d-f7a9b6541c58">
      <Text>Neither is he.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="05a06273-a1d8-4643-9094-76ac470f79bc">
      <Text>A beat. Two. They are looking at the same building from the same angle and both arriving at conclusions through completely different processes.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3ecd4953-9429-4cbc-9d58-10e4765e2bcb">
      <Text>JANET steps into frame between them. She takes the pamphlet from Kevin's hand with accustomed ease. She holds it up. She looks at the photograph. She looks at the building. She tilts the pamphlet slightly. She looks again.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="39656824-c75f-434d-845f-564143cd2baf">
      <Text>Janet hands the pamphlet back to Kevin and steps forward— To where a single side table still stands at the precise coordinates where a lounge chair used to be.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b42eeda7-84b4-4ac3-95c7-e9b3b2d3e619">
      <Text>She crouches. Inspecting the table's edge.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c7452399-889a-4fc2-a1d3-8f44dc6543e5">
      <Text>There: filigree inlay. Decorative metalwork set into the table's apron, intricate, considered, the kind of detail that gets specified by someone who believes the difference between a resort and a hotel is whether anyone bothered with the side tables.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="93c42768-241a-4199-8c21-cd54970f0b4e">
      <Text>Janet looks at it for a long moment.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="e0401d04-3157-44a3-b7ec-dc6a797f42dc">
      <Text>JANET</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="95bed391-4a04-4a21-a4ca-3b7d4d4c6e08">
      <Text>It's got good bones.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="48c7d064-25a2-47f8-9cb4-d01576881910">
      <Text>She stands. She does not look back.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="40922d7b-a2d2-4445-96ba-10822a778bbf">
      <Text>Kevin and Jaz stand where they are.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6eb2dc4c-f61f-400d-99c9-d5b12420f413">
      <Text>Neither of them gives way.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a2446f6c-0839-47cf-b852-8b5474b0c7fc">
      <Text>HUNTER is sitting on the edge of what was once a pool bar— </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a2446f6c-0839-47cf-b852-8b5474b0c7fc">
      <Text>The bar top is still there. The Jameson is almost not.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d94f831a-d2c5-42a2-ab64-48b204a2d06f">
      <Text>He tips the bottle back. A long, considered pull. The second-to-last pull this bottle will ever see. He lowers it. Considers the bottle. Considers the pool. Considers the assembled group.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b8bb34d5-7b2d-4526-967d-72d7a834d344">
      <Text>He extends the bottle toward Kevin and Jaz with the magnanimity of a man who has already decided he doesn't really need the last of it but is willing to explore the possibility.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="bd8e31e2-4a4f-4755-ba2b-473ec41037e4">
      <Text>Kevin shakes his head. A single, small no. The no is not about the whiskey.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5687d4e8-fdba-49dc-8795-74ad7b506dfc">
      <Text>Hunter shrugs. Brings the bottle back. Tips it all the way. Finishes it. Holds the empty for one reflective moment.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1269599f-ca61-4e90-b9a8-5737584879c5">
      <Text>And lobs it gently, underhand, into the pool.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="95889011-e91b-434b-9a4a-8fe4a9b53388">
      <Text>It enters the green water with a small, dignified plunk. Sinks. Joins the chairs.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="331a0d83-d764-46bb-858d-0167977628fd">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="a97fc04a-4f34-404b-b9be-c4f8f0bfda07">
      <Text>Hey.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="5a9e076f-f3dc-4584-8514-7509115f0d25">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="68c1be38-c1f8-4de5-a0a6-6850906da260">
      <Text>(still looking at the pool)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="c506ac76-1441-4a9f-9f91-144353d46bfd">
      <Text>Oh, fuck off.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="c2fad742-9d23-448c-a3a3-c8fbe2ada3f7">
      <Text>(beat)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="4cee8fac-62d8-47a6-a59e-fda4f3e28231">
      <Text>Yeah. That's the thing you'll remember.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="07d7c2f7-e85e-4c2b-90e0-c8c4c02739a0">
      <Text>The bushes at the far edge of the pool deck— the dark, overgrown border where the landscaping concluded nearly a decade ago and the actual woods took over— rustle. Then rustle again with more conviction.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="aa3c551d-c38c-4c82-8041-f0fe7e100895">
      <Text>JAMIE emerges.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="db9f653b-78e7-4112-a6b7-625a5e1e7b01">
      <Text>He is covered in stickers. The burr kind— the small, aggressive, they attach themselves to anything moving through New Jersey underbrush without requesting permission. They are in his hair, on his hoodie, across both legs of his pants, on the backs of his hands. He has a small branch attached to his left shoulder that he has not noticed. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="db9f653b-78e7-4112-a6b7-625a5e1e7b01">
      <Text>His Bodega Nikes — are saturated to approximately mid-lace with something that was ground but now isn't.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d43a1bbb-714c-4adf-9d37-5b6a4330c1d2">
      <Text>He looks like he has been through something extraordinary.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="55002e6d-8340-463d-b1b9-4831ed9182ed">
      <Text>He looks absolutely, precisely, one hundred percent fine with this.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="992ae19a-fd43-40e5-9e9a-06ea7d8fde9f">
      <Text>JAMIE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="6c701015-77f9-477d-97f1-6627ad552289">
      <Text>(no preamble)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="b651b2c0-27d5-4aa8-b6e6-64a15b249779">
      <Text>There's a patio door on one of the rooms over there. Unlocked.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6f142bad-41e4-4b19-bd62-21435a8840fb">
      <Text>He jerks his thumb back toward the dark wing of the building with the ease of someone filing a useful fact.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b2d05e2c-0375-4a76-a2a7-df63f893bedf">
      <Text>Kevin looks at him. Looks at the building. The building is dark and large and has not been inhabited by anything with a lease since the Clinton impeachment.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1693d463-633d-4cd8-8f8a-bced28d2bdd7">
      <Text>He looks around the pool deck. His gaze lands on what was a wooden deck chair. Most of it is there.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a2af8473-b41d-438c-8a4e-f40eee6ac3b8">
      <Text>Kevin reaches down and pulls one of the legs free. It comes off with the resistance of wood that is not structurally sound but still has self-respect. He hefts it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4f1464a7-7103-4b81-a3a5-21e28cd516ce">
      <Text>He holds it in his right hand. He tests the weight. The grip. The kind of primitive calculus a man runs when he is holding a piece of wood in the dark next to a green pool in rural New Jersey at one in the morning.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a2716ded-f163-4aa0-b74b-8563f11ea182">
      <Text>He squares up.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c8ddf0ae-504c-412b-8bf2-da17cb8f7271">
      <Text>He looks at the building.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3ab0c8c1-dcab-4910-8663-1e2506306ac2">
      <Text>He could beat off a grizzly with this. A stuffed one. Maybe a small one — the kind you win at the ring toss if the carny is feeling generous.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0ab3b3f7-35d5-4574-945c-13f98eaaecfc">
      <Text>Jaz looks at him.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="635dbe41-c6d7-421f-bb58-c3115477d851">
      <Text>She takes in the full picture. The dress shoes. The ankle monitor's LED, still green. The wrinkled shirt. His $4000 dollar suit. The chair leg, adjusting position for grip. His belief that this is proportionate response to their current situation.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="cbf41aa4-281d-4e05-a252-9d09a036ade0">
      <Text>A smile flashes across her face. Something she catches almost immediately.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7c76bf2b-8e38-4a7d-a2f6-7be9270aa93c">
      <Text>She looks away before he can see it happen, already moving, already falling into step behind Jamie, messenger bag settling on her hip, boots on the broken pool deck.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="1d98f6e7-d5dc-4983-b287-990028fc897b">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="894ca516-ea01-4c38-b912-cc7787aa1571">
      <Text>(not looking back)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="51bd5a1b-bfa6-4637-bc5a-e2bd94c8522e">
      <Text>Stay here. We'll get the door open.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d99df58e-4f37-434e-bd7c-8feed966ecda">
      <Text>She disappears into the dark after her brother.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3c14e433-36a1-4e6f-9092-61c319f45599">
      <Text>Kevin stands at the edge of the green pool with his chair leg and watches them go.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d0968294-c820-4e7a-932f-b6762b2dd023">
      <Text>He looks at the building.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="93b846e6-e5a4-4f13-8da4-ee3944af2339">
      <Text>He adjusts his grip.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5875ef3d-72b5-42ea-aa8e-57bb4ac145fd">
      <Text>He waits.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="1d07b24d-2de9-4026-8d13-1d9ecfe62b24">
      <SceneProperties Length="4 5/8" Page="25" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="DENNIS">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="PRUITT">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="SANDRA">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="SPECIALIST">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. DENNIS PRUITT'S ROOM - WHARTON, NEW JERSEY - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="37870b5c-a0cf-41dd-8b97-6c682892774e">
      <Text>The back room of a ranch house in Morris County that has been someone's mother's house since 1987 and has not updated its understanding of itself since.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6670ce89-1c56-4245-bf88-21e2cbc1cc02">
      <Text>The wallpaper is a discontinued pattern of small blue flowers. The carpet is the color of a decision made in 1994. The drop ceiling has a water stain in the shape of something that has been there since before Dennis graduated high school and will be there after he dies.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="29786f41-1071-4f8a-a496-19d224928e60">
      <Text>It is still, fundamentally, Dennis Pruitt's childhood bedroom. The evidence is everywhere and is not subtle.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="86fd6373-8837-4914-84ac-1e5a835aa274">
      <Text>A BRUCE SPRINGSTEEN BORN IN THE USA TOUR POSTER, 1984, thumb-tacked to the upper left wall. Curled at the corners. Faded to the specific pink of a thing that has been in indirect sunlight for forty years. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="86fd6373-8837-4914-84ac-1e5a835aa274">
      <Text>Below it, partly obscuring the Boss's legs: a PLASTIC STORAGE BIN full of extension cords and a power strip, shoved against the baseboard with the authority of someone who needed an outlet and did not intend to stay.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="09107a4a-bba8-4574-b857-a75a49c972ec">
      <Text>A VARSITY WRESTLING TROPHY on the shelf above the window. Second place, 1991, Morris County Regional. Dennis Pruitt, 147 </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">lbs</Text>
      <Text>. The little gold man frozen mid-stance for thirty-three years. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="09107a4a-bba8-4574-b857-a75a49c972ec">
      <Text>Next to it: a CVS bag, unopened, containing what the receipt stapled to the outside indicates is athlete's foot cream and one roll of paper towels. The bag has been there long enough to become load-bearing in the shelf's psychology.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c9618c3b-bca8-43d8-854e-39bbbd11e1e6">
      <Text>A BULLETIN BOARD above the desk. This is where the room stops being a teenager's room and becomes something else.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9307c3b0-a560-4c74-86b9-7139e499dde2">
      <Text>Top left, pinned with a red thumbtack: a SCHOOL PHOTO. Two kids. Maybe eight and ten. A boy and a girl, their mother's eyes in both of them. The boy is missing a front tooth and grinning about it. The girl has her hair in the specific configuration of a child who has fixed her own hair and is proud of it. The photo has a crease across one corner, the kind you get when something has been folded and unfolded too many times.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f84c3a51-8dbe-4265-925e-b436eb3ad388">
      <Text>Next to it, pinned with a blue thumbtack that does not match: a WEDDING PHOTOGRAPH. Dennis and a woman, mid-nineties, outdoors. Dennis with more hair and less face. The woman laughing at something off-camera, her hand on Dennis's arm, her face turned just enough that you can see she is genuinely, completely happy in this moment. It is the most human Dennis Pruitt has ever looked. He is not looking at the camera. He is looking at her.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="51a79d5f-adb2-4ee2-b092-ccd2b2908840">
      <Text>Below the wedding photo, pinned to the board with a BUCK KNIFE driven through it to the hilt: a LEGAL DOCUMENT. The blade goes through the signature page. SUPERIOR COURT OF NEW JERSEY, MORRIS COUNTY. FINAL JUDGMENT OF DIVORCE. SOLE CUSTODY awarded to LINDA PRUITT. Child support. Alimony. The monthly figures visible if you look. Dennis has looked. Dennis has them memorized in the way you memorize things that take something from you every month.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4a1829d0-0be2-4a97-b262-d6870c04a271">
      <Text>The buck knife was his father's. It is the most deliberate thing in the room.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="986ff3be-f0d1-4586-83d1-7679b68dfefa">
      <Text>Against the far wall: a folding table serving as a desk. Two monitors. The setup has the energy of something assembled from components purchased separately over several years on a county employee's salary, each piece slightly incompatible with the others in a way that requires one specific startup sequence that Dennis has memorized and will die with him.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1ffaf7aa-a968-432a-96cb-ddca5a7794b6">
      <Text>The LEFT MONITOR: the NEW JERSEY PRETRIAL SERVICES MONITORING INTERFACE. State-issued software, designed in 2009, never substantially updated. Gray background. A map of Sussex County. Two GREEN DOTS, stationary, on the same property. They arrived at 12:07 AM and have not moved.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="eae13551-9185-40e0-b735-6f38c7cb9ab3">
      <Text>The RIGHT MONITOR: six browser tabs. New York Post. Times. Bloomberg. LinkedIn. A Hampton charity gala photograph from a society column — KEVIN McCORT in black tie, JANET McCORT beside him, both of them luminous in the way of people for whom photographs have always been cooperative.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3d4cc5dc-b2c0-41a0-afbc-4da0fb51e800">
      <Text>Dennis is not reading. He has read all of it. He is looking at it the way you look at evidence.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3dda1cfc-cc98-4eb9-8cd2-809dc26503a0">
      <Text>He is in a desk chair that came with the house, in his Sussex County Pretrial Services polo and a pair of sweatpants, which is not an outfit that suggests he planned to be awake at this hour. He has not been to sleep. He will not go to sleep. The room is too quiet without the television and too loud with it and neither version produces sleep.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5f735fbe-592c-4793-82b9-13747232aa39">
      <Text>On the floor beside the chair: a gas station coffee cup, cold. A Sudoku book, face-down on a page that has been dog-eared for three weeks. His reading glasses, one arm repaired with a rubber band.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4fe563fb-be46-4de1-9c35-b8d04b14d017">
      <Text>On the wall above the monitors, hung with a single pushpin, slightly off-center: a LAMINATED PHOTOGRAPH. Not a plaque. A photograph of a plaque, cut to fit the lamination sleeve by hand, the edges not quite even. SUSSEX COUNTY PRETRIAL SERVICES OFFICER OF THE YEAR — 2019.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7eec3fae-c816-429d-a7d4-00a2dd5c0131">
      <Text>He was runner-up in 2018. There is no photograph of that.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b0fcc937-ea1c-43f4-8908-748e743c0f0b">
      <Text>On the television in the corner: HOARDERS. Volume low. A WOMAN in Missouri standing in a kitchen that is not visible as a kitchen because of what is in it. A SPECIALIST in a polo shirt is speaking to her with the careful voice of someone who has learned through professional training to deliver information that feels like weather.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="72b6c0af-48e1-4a19-9248-32dd990e88f4">
      <Text>SPECIALIST (ON TV)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="e3970ba3-ed04-40f1-b4e3-d181e99b8464">
      <Text>Sandra, I want you to understand that we're not here to take anything from you. We just need you to help us understand what's-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="3339610e-2448-441e-87e5-cf74e6bcd231">
      <Text>DENNIS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="818c61fd-ad65-40aa-a511-e105bdffaeb7">
      <Text>(not looking at the TV, reciting it)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="8790947e-3d8b-48c1-b826-2bcd7a1bcec2">
      <Text>...what's important. What we can work with.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="1ee70fd5-d52c-4b9c-ae40-24d9638b19a2">
      <Text>SPECIALIST (ON TV)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="c82db788-aa63-4b15-a085-8ec506e8c115">
      <Text>...what's important. What we can work with.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="91431a58-944d-43ab-8cad-a5f170d79841">
      <Text>Dennis takes a sip of the cold coffee. Does not react to the temperature.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="472089f7-5daf-4474-a867-872225ad4e4d">
      <Text>SANDRA (ON TV)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="295e342e-2ca4-443e-96af-29d6811c0833">
      <Text>These were my mother's. Every single one of these was my mother's, and I am not going to just-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="f69a7b7b-4292-4a44-b489-90534c7d39b5">
      <Text>DENNIS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="0a1934f7-fe21-4395-81b9-46dcec686d40">
      <Text>(monotone, a beat ahead)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="098ba21b-0ceb-41b6-bb09-fe4987f05bca">
      <Text>...let some stranger come in here and tell me what has value.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="d2bf55d5-54fa-4964-9bf8-58249feb934d">
      <Text>SANDRA (ON TV)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="fb4e261c-b48c-4665-965c-5da7f77c84bb">
      <Text>...let some stranger come in here and tell me what has value.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="eb9ef888-70e2-4228-85fc-1fc1b1285091">
      <Text>Dennis sets the coffee down. Looks at the RIGHT MONITOR. Finds the Bloomberg photograph. Kevin McCort in the corner office. The skyline. The </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">Patek</Text>
      <Text> Phillippe catching light in a way that suggests the photographer knew what they were doing.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6fe64db1-2baa-46dd-92d7-3da8d4c858bd">
      <Text>He looks at this for a moment.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0073fe7a-8352-44fa-b816-d791fc8a0b45">
      <Text>Then he picks up his phone. Opens the recent calls log.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="76df87b8-9987-4a59-babc-0aa0d18f3187">
      <Text>11:45 AM. The call from a 212 area code. Four minutes and eleven seconds.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="0f33fe1a-27b2-41e4-947b-313e8014406f">
      <Text>Pruitt</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="a8378823-44ce-48da-8e89-9007e8365423">
      <Text>(hard to hear through the chip on his shoulder)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="3398c574-612c-40e3-bc1b-98f9a5844e24">
      <Text>Section 4c- Hah! Like I don't know exactly what you fucking sleazes try to get away with in section 4c.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="348c46f7-f2c4-49ee-b706-5251cd616aeb">
      <Text>Dennis opens the contact screen. Creates a new entry.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9c41d2ae-93e4-4dbc-afd2-c4cd54f61a4d">
      <Text>The NAME field, reads: HUNTER REID</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9c41d2ae-93e4-4dbc-afd2-c4cd54f61a4d">
      <Text>In the COMPANY field, he types: ASSHOLE LAWYER for ASSHOLE MCCORT.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4650a84c-e154-4459-8946-cbee1c12c714">
      <Text>He saves the contact. Sets the phone face-down on the desk next to the cold coffee.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c4f7d315-1656-4670-bde7-f0aea777fdef">
      <Text>He looks at the LEFT MONITOR. The two green dots. Stationary. 12:10 AM on the state system clock in the upper right corner.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5639cb57-7fa0-46d9-a6ad-5f92102d277e">
      <Text>He pulls up the booking portal in a new tab. Types the case number from memory. Two mugshots load. Side by side. Gray background.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="db881e29-2e1e-4281-b71e-eaa4c16aebdd">
      <Text>KEVIN McCORT, left. The suit. The look of a man who has not yet fully accepted the news.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a7adfc64-3400-439e-b3a6-a963b478ecd5">
      <Text>JANET McCORT, right.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c148c574-c7f8-44c3-8deb-a44f37499d1e">
      <Text>Lululemon. Hair still in that configuration. No makeup. The booking light finding her face with the cooperation of someone who has never once in her adult life taken a bad photograph, including apparently this one, which is a mugshot, taken at eight in the morning, after a sunrise arrest, and she still looks like the woman from the Hampton gala.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="dc40c774-a8e9-4c2d-84e1-39c6a54f9df9">
      <Text>Dennis looks at the right monitor. At the gala photograph. At the booking photo. Back at the gala photograph.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="1f63ff63-b7e6-480a-bb7f-80bd5237e8f3">
      <Text>SANDRA (ON TV)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="17784f1b-a1e5-42e1-af37-90b464c2de40">
      <Text>I know it looks like a lot. I know how it looks. But every one of these meant something to someone, and that doesn't just—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="ee16613b-8862-41aa-a601-fc3d7f84979c">
      <Text>DENNIS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="9e79ff5c-92f0-4dd8-a661-55c10b663a30">
      <Text>(to the monitors, quietly, still a beat ahead)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="ce905d95-4f42-4a84-a40a-5f4de7ff560f">
      <Text>...go away because you decide it does.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="fac91997-d2a8-4412-95a8-8d85587acdec">
      <Text>SANDRA (ON TV)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="c439a185-1be2-4eb3-9499-8ba6a589260c">
      <Text>...go away because you decide it does.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d3d047d4-19cd-4711-bdd6-8b7e92523863">
      <Text>He reaches over. Adjusts the right monitor slightly left. The gala photograph moves to center. Janet McCort in something that cost more than his monthly take-home, her hand light on Kevin's arm, her face turned toward something off-camera that has made her genuinely, completely—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3e09609d-e531-4464-9c61-b961dc00e56e">
      <Text>The two green dots pulse on the left monitor. Stationary. On property. In compliance.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d754a7c7-d508-4161-9f6d-0a8c3d06db08">
      <Text>He centers her mugshot on the left monitor, zooms it in. Makes eye contact with as if she were looking at him rather than the mug shot camera lens.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="117a2592-c433-4115-af96-3f4f8c2e1301">
      <Text>He reaches up and pulls a old sullen pair of stained women's floral print panties from the desk under his monitor's edge.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e60ac0bf-5c6e-4bea-b449-d02e60323e48">
      <Text>Moves them to his lap as he slide down the waist band of his sweatpants.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="2725e070-4250-49b5-806c-057c67a13294">
      <Text>PRUITT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="4bb7bb4b-0f70-469f-aaca-ee91b95fd9c1">
      <Text>(to Janet's image)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="1d95a694-21fc-4497-9d0b-2990595d4fbd">
      <Text>Yeah, you like to watch, you slut. I'll show you what a real man can make you feel.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="de62976e-8056-4bd7-97d2-3a86e005e42b">
      <Text>The specialist on television is explaining, with practiced gentleness, that the structure is no longer sound.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="5923d322-7b6f-4aba-94b9-aed261d00545">
      <SceneProperties Length="1 7/8" Page="30" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAMIE">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAZ">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>EXT. PLAYBOY RESORT - EAST WING - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="bde38c09-6a7c-4a00-803c-9e59336d63ed">
      <Text>The landscaping that once defined the east wing's private patio corridor has for a long time taken it's own authority.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="bde38c09-6a7c-4a00-803c-9e59336d63ed">
      <Text>The hedges that used to separate each ground floor suite's patio have grown together into a single continuous wall of dark green that has consumed the iron dividers and the original paving stones and whatever else was in the way. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="bde38c09-6a7c-4a00-803c-9e59336d63ed">
      <Text>The concrete pathway along the building's face is still under there somewhere. Under the roots, leaves, the moss, and the ground cover that moved in after the concrete decided it was tired of being concrete.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d5a3e46c-2cda-4ff0-b4b8-d2da573772bf">
      <Text>Jaz and Jamie are moving through the bramble in single file. Jamie first, making way with his forearms, the burr situation on his hoodie entering a new and ambitious phase. His Nikes are doing their best.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c9188d96-dfa2-42c1-9783-b7e12cc0a8e8">
      <Text>The east wing's ground floor runs along their left. Through the moss and dirt smeared on the floor-to-ceiling patio glass: darkness and wreckage.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1eb13433-4d03-4f38-be62-8b314f42c368">
      <Text>Jaz can see it in the phone light that angles off the glass as they move. Rooms stripped to their bones. Steel stud framing running in grids where walls used to be. Concrete subfloor. Conduit running overhead. The renovation that stopped in the middle of itself and never resumed.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c7556096-f5b8-4f55-9081-7a13fb57c026">
      <Text>And the toilets.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="63dea04e-f1e2-4ba8-8977-b4517cbd863e">
      <Text>There are dozens of them. Porcelain white, still connected to their rough-in plumbing, standing at intervals throughout the skeletal space like sentinels. Each one in what used to be a bathroom of a suite that no longer has walls, standing in the open air of the stripped floor plan, formal and baffled and faintly absurd. Some upright. One tipped slightly, still connected, listing like a drunk trying to maintain dignity.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8839d562-c2fb-400c-8c8e-8951a46601f6">
      <Text>Jaz takes all of this in through the glass while she walks. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="110ca8d2-bff9-44df-ac34-3323155a7460">
      <Text>Jaz's body movements do what they always do in spaces like this-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text> Phoenix is electrified with the specific energy of a person who has just been handed something rather than had something taken.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="6f7c3a1e-4f94-46f6-b9d0-a558f0f7ffe7">
      <Text>JAMIE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="47136efd-b9e1-49cc-a3a3-653b10ea1917">
      <Text>(stopping)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="b3faf8a0-78a3-4954-bd60-5b4e700b8891">
      <Text>Here.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2cfdad1d-bdf5-499d-b813-7b38b29ca022">
      <Text>The sliding glass patio door. Third panel from the corner of the wing. In the frame at an angle-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>barely, just enough. A centimeter gap at the top right corner where the panel has settled off its track and the latch can no longer find its receiver.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9a9c5050-245e-479b-96db-2cda9ce9ad10">
      <Text>Jamie gets his fingers into the edge and pulls.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="64c21cd0-92d2-4d51-b2cf-69bac1806576">
      <Text>The door doesn't move.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="72b89b79-e202-4423-9dc8-b627d8707921">
      <Text>He repositions. Tries the other direction. The door shifts slightly, grinds, catches. He tries again.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="6e268c58-fa8d-48bc-90aa-7cb7d556db5e">
      <Text>JAMIE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="1a7946d6-094e-41ce-b939-5b6d0d9b0441">
      <Text>It's stuck.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ad471f7a-16bd-42c2-8b7b-38b1a5c9e815">
      <Text>She puts one hand on his shoulder and moves him gently to the side. He goes. She looks at the door for a moment the way a skilled craftsmen already know what to do.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="742b7b4d-ba3d-409c-a067-d2e3b2c4b8ee">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="f8c16185-7f9c-4e6f-a87c-5396355c5da8">
      <Text>Let me show you how this is done.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5e31794a-5f80-415c-9798-3c8c9b99de10">
      <Text>She raises both palms flat. Places them against the glass near the top of the panel. Not forcing it. Feeling it. Then she leans in -</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>not a push, a shift, her whole weight moving at a specific angle, lifting the panel fractionally up and back at the same time, the geometry of it working with the door's physics instead of against them-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4e0c9358-f67f-4b6c-8471-fd8b09065733">
      <Text>The panel moves. Smooth. Then free.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8d7fca76-0f40-432d-851a-20c3326d3816">
      <Text>The gap opens.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a0f1ecc0-ffa3-4e2a-9673-aa494f034faf">
      <Text>Jamie looks at the door. Then at her.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="cf67cd9d-9968-4220-be6e-37e2c4a98290">
      <Text>Jamie</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="f642dcbe-161c-4ecc-b1f4-cdcd07e133be">
      <Text>So- you've done this allot. Breaking into abandoned places.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="c1916dd7-9836-4c6d-bded-fcf6854f826f">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="0b0e753f-56b0-4b82-b9de-cc1312e863a7">
      <Text>(already through)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="721245ef-b35c-48ca-86ea-83a51f371084">
      <Text>Come on.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="f267f5f4-4f42-42da-8d0e-b91b08ebd146">
      <SceneProperties Length="3 3/8" Page="31" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAMIE">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAZ">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - EAST WING - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="667eb4d0-dec7-486c-b5c7-1c0e09cd6bd9">
      <Text>The dark inside is a different animal than the dark outside.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="dca74fb7-9fdf-4490-82f3-6f9e4cfd3522">
      <Text>Outside was just night. In here the dark has been a long time settling and you can feel it. It has the texture that of being sealed with itself for years, and it carries the specific smell of concrete and old air and something organic moving slowly through the walls.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ba75478b-d386-4e20-95a0-b958281bd6be">
      <Text>The phone's light is the only light there is. Jamie holds it up and the beam goes into the space and the space gives back shadows-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>the steel framing racking them in long angular shapes across the concrete floor, multiplying as the beam moves, the geometry shifting and doubling and crossing itself. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ba75478b-d386-4e20-95a0-b958281bd6be">
      <Text>The toilets catch the light and hold it, white and patient and strange, dozens of them, standing in the open ruins of their former context. Here. Here. Here and here and here. All the way back as far as the beam can reach and probably further.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="12411129-fe11-4300-83b7-3cf6541c1770">
      <Text>A door hangs in a frame in the middle of the space. Nothing on either side of it anymore. Just the frame, the hinges, the door. It swings slightly as the air comes in behind them.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="61518d66-3ab0-41bf-9077-247d726c42f7">
      <Text>Jaz floats with the easy proprietary of someone walking into a room they've been in a thousand times in a thousand different abandoned buildings. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="61518d66-3ab0-41bf-9077-247d726c42f7">
      <Text>Combat boots on abandoned concrete.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5d789140-6475-4c49-9c00-3973547a86b6">
      <Text>She's reading the space as she goes- not the damage and liability-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>she floats and glides in the infinite pool of potential.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e5fbba0d-e382-4ee2-b417-f67036097022">
      <Text>She is entirely, completely at home.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="30b04700-5b92-4664-b605-ff87667f6a5e">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="203cd9a5-6f5d-49e4-8a2a-3d266b000b05">
      <Text>(under her breath)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="8e277f9e-0690-491a-8e93-1098b632f56a">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">Yeeeesssss</Text>
      <Text>-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="67e408fa-730c-4a44-8e79-2c068b1e1537">
      <Text>This is her church.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="67e408fa-730c-4a44-8e79-2c068b1e1537">
      <Text>She points at the electrical conduit where it rests, running low across the floor where someone pulled it down from the ceiling and never re-routed it. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="4841c935-5852-45b8-93fc-3574f954953d">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="7acbdff6-0db0-4b22-9d3d-b0c37dd3be48">
      <Text>(reflexively to Jamie)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="a48019b8-d62c-4922-a21f-346b4b8c0318">
      <Text>Watch the traps.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="67e408fa-730c-4a44-8e79-2c068b1e1537">
      <Text>Jamie steps over it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d12f5835-e579-4c8c-b221-5f24d7035b46">
      <Text>They go deeper. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d12f5835-e579-4c8c-b221-5f24d7035b46">
      <Text>The beam moves with them. The toilets appear and recede. The hanging door turns slowly in the air behind them. The steel framing opens up where corridors used to meet and closes again where walls used to be and the whole thing has a quality of a space that was halfway through becoming something else and got frozen there.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c216b261-1166-4a0b-8cbe-a0bbed50ec96">
      <Text>Jaz is listening to the room.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="30a0f73f-71fd-4309-9281-10f6e505042f">
      <Text>Jamie walks beside her.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b2dc2c46-e7f8-4ec8-bfa1-3980e99123c8">
      <Text>Then behind her.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9d12c804-da1f-4d3a-9bce-322d7b99d800">
      <Text>Then he slows.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="439066be-36e8-422c-9800-e860413a4cd5">
      <Text>Jaz walks three more steps before she notices. She turns.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="338fd781-816a-411b-8bcc-a71724c09131">
      <Text>Jamie is stopped in a gap between two frames. The phone in his hand, pointing down. The light hitting the concrete between them. His face is not its usual face.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e6de1eba-11ed-465d-aac2-5147271546ad">
      <Text>He is fourteen. He has been fine since this morning. Since the handcuffs on the sidewalk and the ACS waiting room and the barefoot linoleum and the diner and the Civic and the ankle alarm counting down through the trees. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e6de1eba-11ed-465d-aac2-5147271546ad">
      <Text>He has been fine through all of it he understood that fine was the correct operational setting and has not deviated.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="057564c7-35ab-46ae-adaf-5a4a3ca7d8f2">
      <Text>But he is 14.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="54747c67-6586-4e03-93a7-bbf8dfd04147">
      <Text>He is standing in the dark gut of a building nobody has lived in since before he was born, and he is not fine.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="9101ea6b-a466-4c3f-ad18-cb084bccfadc">
      <Text>JAMIE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="8cb65bb6-b982-4772-bbb3-3af45972bddc">
      <Text>(quietly, looking at the floor)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="160a6895-a915-47de-9f83-c0d5dff7c407">
      <Text>Are we OK here?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="d3961e1d-9894-413f-8a54-63180a1e4b2e">
      <Text>(beat)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="269c9f51-5cd3-46f3-ba8d-790f5ec038ab">
      <Text>Are mom and dad going to be okay?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="68da2db7-1408-4c07-af8a-245b57de02e5">
      <Text>Combat boots step into the beam of light of the phone pointed to the ground. Toe to toe with the bodega Nikes.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="98bd10bb-e175-4303-ba12-3e800dd50dbf">
      <Text>She kneels down. Eye to eye.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="c3282d6e-9ff9-4e2f-a4a4-d82aa2fbe857">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="90b2d772-663f-44c7-8b58-e08f7705e1bb">
      <Text>I became me in rooms like this one.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="eda2d219-e410-4b0d-994a-a9ab4f0c3856">
      <Text>He looks up.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="149ecf10-a382-4d0b-af8c-7e12cec6e4c1">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="b557f528-19e3-4eff-b6cf-e60ca496754f">
      <Text>Boarded up, gutted, no lights, no heat. Places that used to be something and weren't anymore. Me and a pile of people crammed in with a generator and a PA and everybody completely sure that whatever was about to happen was going to be the realest thing that happened this week.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="673385f3-9fde-4444-80a9-34c4c55b9fdd">
      <Text>(beat)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="8be58e1f-ac97-47b4-81cc-512e7300c0e7">
      <Text>These rooms were the only places I ever felt fully free and like myself. Like the whole real thing of me could just unfold and be be born anew each time and nobody was going to ask me to be something else.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9e8b8507-2e82-4361-9fad-cd994452a133">
      <Text>She looks around at the steel bones of the east wing. The toilets in the dark. The door turning on its hinges.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="35fd6396-1c36-4074-ba27-29480527f968">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="fb4cd242-2c2a-474b-8c17-740f697209e6">
      <Text>I don't know what happens to mom and dad. I don't know what this looks like on the other side. Nobody does.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="98df9e05-7ab1-414b-b80b-5d2e04e16db3">
      <Text>(beat)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="3a7206e1-e715-41bc-a661-9243b3dacd24">
      <Text>But this? This is ours. Whatever we do with the shape it, whatever the shape ends up being -</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>it will be us inside it. That doesn't go away.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="08e7923c-7490-4811-9089-451392756c5f">
      <Text>Jamie looks at her. He is running this through in his head.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="7e82f736-e9de-4713-93b1-5b2d73e5c9c0">
      <Text>JAMIE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="8e0a2bed-f71c-4375-9c78-2d0a1e4d7336">
      <Text>You actually believe that.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="4cea90c5-950f-4390-821c-1241b9c76d4c">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="507945e7-5983-4824-a356-08b65407f6be">
      <Text>(not a question, not a performance)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="b34135e6-f956-4090-aff5-1d066319d8e4">
      <Text>Yeah. I do.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="991b9eb1-a677-4445-83ee-fb4a3a58471e">
      <Text>(fire burning in her eyes)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="c396d448-505b-4604-8d9f-47464cc2367f">
      <Text>This is mine. Which means it's ours.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="94a5adda-38b8-4ce8-9612-2b68890a29c6">
      <Text>A beat. The door behind them turns.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e8927f91-8deb-4ecd-bf3d-b1060d7589f4">
      <Text>Jamie looks at the space around them. At the framing. At the toilets in their rows, patient and surreal in the dark. At the conduit running overhead. At the depth of the building still in front of them, still waiting to be known.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2a466032-007e-43b9-9700-9a114d8ec897">
      <Text>Something in him settles. Not all the way. Enough.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="63c4b8df-3933-45cd-8c21-e0837d95fea2">
      <Text>He raises the phone. The beam goes forward into the dark.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="690d4803-a4c0-4a18-ada9-8f7adb5cc195">
      <Text>JAMIE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="b4c0f075-8b05-4105-9067-f628ab046844">
      <Text>What do you think is in the middle.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="5e5bafef-f0f9-4b69-98c8-b126c66e1141">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="d89fb7b2-4d6f-4dec-9321-9d5fd2041d01">
      <Text>(already floating that way)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Dialogue" id="568c8956-6c91-4bd2-9ed9-6c44cdcaf705">
      <Text>Let's find out.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a243c8fc-ec64-4922-9f18-f53f7e55772c">
      <Text>He falls into step beside her. The light moves with them. The shadows rack and shift ahead.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e60e081a-2ecc-47e3-9b1e-500612be97ea">
      <Text>Behind them, the sliding glass door they came through sits open in its warped track. The midnight air finds the gap. Moves through the skeleton framing. Lifts the hanging door slightly on its hinges.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f0e21502-598d-4715-a512-2a1478e15f24">
      <Text>The building breathes.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="9be8e160-8ea1-402f-97ee-31f8db0d2001">
      <SceneProperties Length="1 5/8" Page="35" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JANET">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="KEVIN">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>EXT. PLAYBOY RESORT - POOL DECK - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="bcafb0b0-287e-4c37-8086-ce0c8260fb37">
      <Text>Kevin stands at the pool's edge, head tilted back. Taking in the full scale of the building against the sky. Eight story roofline. The sheer dark volume of it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="62128c8f-2a1d-4d1e-89b1-8ce1d0bd28b2">
      <Text>In his right hand — the broken chair leg from earlier. His grip shifts on it. Loosens. Tightens. Loosens. The unconscious rhythm of a hand that needs something to hold.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="95e3972e-bb22-40ec-8260-ae7e39c9d5f6">
      <Text>His jaw is working.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7643aa11-9c36-4f1e-a481-b1ba85d20d7e">
      <Text>Forty feet behind him, at the tiki bar — what's left of it — Hunter is folded over the counter. Head on his arms. His breathing has the cadence of a man who lost the argument with consciousness minutes ago.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e9779cfc-efec-401d-a3e1-94aa4239ed6f">
      <Text>Footsteps on concrete. Kevin doesn't turn. Doesn't need to.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="38561dfc-bc65-49a7-ac71-d7689df130cb">
      <Text>Janet stops a few feet behind him. Arms wrapped around herself. The midnight air doing what midnight air does in the Jersey highlands.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b088dda9-69c2-46dc-b6d9-19c1290b6e7f">
      <Text>She watches him. The set of his shoulders. The specific stillness. The chair leg turning slowly in his grip— not brandished, not raised. Held the way a man holds something when his hands need occupation or they'll do something his brain hasn't approved.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="99fe4186-8113-432c-89af-ac9d80592c84">
      <Text>She knows he saw the phone. The picture. The length of the text history.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="79fafdd6-390d-44b2-b4d1-686d1486a4c8">
      <Text>A beat.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="3f93ec87-1582-4599-9b28-692ac5247e0e">
      <Text>JANET</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="0eb581cc-15b1-4d0c-a0e1-600eb7bad90d">
      <Text>Kevin.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b3f16500-7c01-4f22-a480-31663dcc5565">
      <Text>Nothing. The grip adjusts. The Jaw works.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="922b56f5-a299-4653-9a31-6a9aab5b9b9c">
      <Text>JANET</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="959a1af6-6cf4-45c6-ab01-02bf2b86387b">
      <Text>Kev.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="cee0ee46-d23a-46c7-b629-8c5bcf82d7d8">
      <Text>The jaw stops working. This is worse.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f0a29e58-4ab6-4f7d-a106-1ea2977393e8">
      <Text>He turns his head. Not his body. Just his head.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="31209dc5-f50d-4ae7-b039-fa2ab4b0553e">
      <Text>His eyes find hers.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d620b6c3-3733-4c7d-b13f-c94b7022172f">
      <Text>Janet has been looked at by this man for twenty-two years. She has never seen this. Not anger— A thing way past anger. A thing that happens when something burns so hot it stops giving off light.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="74e6f8ec-29cd-4654-8585-44f5de0d48ca">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="023140c5-4519-4bcb-a209-cf5877075ca7">
      <Text>(very quiet, very even)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="7b66dae9-27cb-4f9f-984f-aad22bd3875a">
      <Text>You need to find a lawyer.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7f7651c6-aa26-4da9-a4ed-9d37aec6c6fc">
      <Text>She blinks. Reads him. She looks for the only version of Kevin she has ever scene— the one who fixes, who manages, who folds every problem into an operational framework and moves forward.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7544d613-8918-4fb8-a945-69a510188d24">
      <Text>This Kevin is not there. And what stands in front of the terrifies her.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="e824eb1f-5a00-4449-86b1-ca20c40a0616">
      <Text>JANET</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="d533d999-23ba-4ef0-8246-d02bc8cfff08">
      <Text>(careful)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="65c5c75e-37d0-4987-8e0c-45c27d7d9662">
      <Text>You mean for the case?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="eb2821fb-45f4-4d65-b59f-9beeb9cf2491">
      <Text>Kevin holds her gaze. Doesn't blink. The chair leg has gone still in his hand.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="08d89fc6-70cc-48df-9bf9-d2860d9caa18">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="da93508a-e2f9-4281-8667-7f37b686aae6">
      <Text>For that too.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="29beeb56-9bc8-45cd-a082-b63b75947acb">
      <Text>He turns back to the building.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d3209cea-e572-4742-8330-e90a828e0ffa">
      <Text>Janet stands there. Her arms tighten. Not against the cold.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="67f51057-7e87-48ea-8328-231bdf592ffc">
      <Text>At the bar, Hunter shifts. His hand slides off the edge. He doesn't wake.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5ea0157e-dfd4-4928-93ac-56df48bc50cc">
      <Text>Kevin's grip finds the chair leg again. Adjusts. The monitor blinks green on his ankle.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="d2098692-3538-4dfd-9ea5-8e2d98d7996f">
      <SceneProperties Length="2/8" Page="36" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats/>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - EAST WING - GROUND FLOOR - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a45dfb55-bbd3-47f4-8801-1c1b1096d021">
      <Text>Jaz and Jamie moving deeper. The phone light catching steel studs and toilets and nothing else. The demolition runs the full length of the wing — uninterrupted, gutted, all the way to the end.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="79b5bd44-4268-4cb4-8f33-7d11a76a6ead">
      <Text>The space finally terminates. Fire doors. Heavy gauge steel. No windows. The boundary between what was torn apart and what was left alone.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3cc4de05-e44c-41d5-a939-2fe24e4b2e99">
      <Text>Jaz pushes through.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="f050d82c-f80f-47c6-a00a-70b887f550e3">
      <SceneProperties Length="3/8" Page="37" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats/>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - EAST WING STAIRWELL - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="365034e9-8483-4433-bdea-2c30697c1c3a">
      <Text>Orange carpet. Solid orange. No pattern, no variation. Just a flat aggressive commitment to a color that 1972 believed in completely.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b94d836e-a47c-47b6-9e98-1b9f682bf73f">
      <Text>It runs up the treads between beige walls and copper-trimmed handrails gone green with oxidation.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="992fc518-8fd5-46f6-9020-9be5a7cccd47">
      <Text>Their footsteps go silent on it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f6ccdb0b-1fc8-49c4-923b-02e44ad8d66c">
      <Text>Two flights. The orange holds.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9233d244-585f-4f4c-b3cf-741584447842">
      <Text>Another set of fire doors at the top. Steel. No glass. No indication of what's on the other side.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="30db7ca0-2803-46f5-aa54-a1a062d2b00a">
      <Text>Jaz pushes through.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="5a8270c6-2517-471b-aba0-38708bd010fd">
      <SceneProperties Length="5/8" Page="37" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats/>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - MAIN BUILDING - THIRD FLOOR CORRIDOR - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2477e1e6-f91c-497c-b649-11db802c9e6d">
      <Text>The carpet changes under her feet.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="cd537178-7f29-49b0-a48a-65ea1fe38ffe">
      <Text>Green. Deep green. And on it — a geometric pattern that repeats and repeats and repeats. Diamonds inside diamonds inside diamonds, beige and green and brown, tessellating in every direction with the obsessive confidence of a design choice that predates the concept of restraint.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3075ef5b-9846-482e-95c1-4d82ba745fdd">
      <Text>The corridor runs wide ahead of them. Normal ceiling height. Planters along one side — wooden, square, whatever was in them reduced to dry sticks and powder. The walls carry muted pink accents between stone-faced columns.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f43e5f3e-3195-40e6-b779-66085a7bb732">
      <Text>Dark. No power. The phone light catches the pattern on the carpet and for a second the repeating geometry appears to shift and breathe in the moving beam.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3ef6b4d4-48ef-437b-9beb-9ebe118975c9">
      <Text>They walk. A hundred feet of corridor. The carpet pattern refusing to stop.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2e4ff3ed-5c1e-45c0-a936-1612ee6a7df0">
      <Text>Then the ceiling lifts.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="bb6005a7-b962-4776-bd38-abbb34738f77">
      <Text>It lifts and lifts and then it's glass.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="9feb4ec7-d470-48ba-9288-c04a594a804a">
      <SceneProperties Length="1 3/8" Page="38" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAMIE">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAZ">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - SIDEWALK CAFÉ - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6bb8a7f2-af5a-47bd-8d27-fc9e7eb8e513">
      <Text>Moonlight.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f85bf315-c26e-4b3c-9018-524ca6e3cdce">
      <Text>It falls through the glass ceiling and fills the space below with the specific blue-white of a Sussex County midnight, and what it fills is enormous.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="230bcb19-e088-4e24-a5f7-42796b91ce06">
      <Text>The Sidewalk Café opens off the corridor like a piazza — tables and chairs still set across the geometric carpet, wicker diamond-pattern chairs at four-tops, darker wooden chairs at two-tops, all of it arranged around a sunken path of green tile that winds through the seating in a wide lazy curve.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="95e38508-1fe1-4237-8e88-d1e835b49519">
      <Text>Wrought iron street lamps line the tile path on both sides. Dead. But standing in formation, their glass fixtures catching the moonlight from above, throwing faint shadows across the tables like sundials running on the wrong light.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a16fc910-75d3-48f2-819a-8b8390aa58cc">
      <Text>In the center of the green tile channel — an island. A tree. Still alive somehow, growing toward the glass ceiling above it, its branches reaching into the moonlight like it's been waiting for someone to show up and explain what happened to everyone else.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="41f410fa-c425-40d6-9778-0e5d543e4c4c">
      <Text>The stone feature wall rises behind it all. Massive. Raw. The kind of thing that was designed to look like nature and ended up looking like what money thinks nature is.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a9b88e29-004d-4d80-810f-abd116121d08">
      <Text>Jamie lowers the phone. He doesn't need it here. The moon is doing the work.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2e96be36-c7e9-4498-b241-ed4fcf981efa">
      <Text>Jaz stands at the edge of the café. The geometric carpet under her boots. The moonlit tables ahead. The tree.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a5b90cab-d013-468f-97c2-265b5aed16e5">
      <Text>She doesn't say anything. She turns slowly. Taking in the volume of it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="24b16c71-41af-48da-a96f-8f57063797a6">
      <Text>Jamie turns with her. Past the café. Past the stone wall.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f24f0655-e9dd-432b-8e07-c553e9c94304">
      <Text>Glass. A wall of it. And on the other side — the indoor pool. Empty. Pale basin. Depth markings on the walls. NO DIVING. A single metal chair on the deck.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f0ac99db-7ba7-45f7-aa24-feae15d172f6">
      <Text>And through the far glass of the pool room — exterior glass, looking out into the night—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="56f72d27-63f7-4b4d-9738-c6d50d6fe61b">
      <Text>The outdoor pool deck. Concrete. Chain link. Moonlight.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a04a75dc-fc84-4b32-89f7-363d962c5d5a">
      <Text>Two figures on the far side.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5b298919-b695-46be-be44-20d262a94318">
      <Text>Kevin at the pool's edge. The chair leg in his hand.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d556d795-dd25-4cc8-94e2-0e7e7c731720">
      <Text>Janet behind him. Arms crossed.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="5c3aafc8-4cb3-40dc-83d6-4e3cd3393f96">
      <Text>JAMIE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="350ff552-43e5-41aa-9a9b-b5754a7b3d63">
      <Text>(quiet)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="d5152dcb-e936-46fc-860d-54503c262e00">
      <Text>Mom and Dad.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a120f05e-8aa9-4767-88b8-7e37fdb7dc87">
      <Text>Jaz looks. Forty yards away. Two walls of glass and an empty pool between them.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ed3dabc8-c56b-4e0e-a7a1-c28e0bdb40d3">
      <Text>She watches. The way Kevin is standing. The way Janet is standing behind him. The distance between them.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="6aa3e46a-113a-42ef-8549-01a6e5960ac9">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="8ec8b09e-007d-4191-b65b-12eaf95841c4">
      <Text>Come on. Let's find the door and bring them inside.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="df05c419-a00d-4c5d-bb84-6154fa79af70">
      <Text>She turns back into the corridor. Combat boots on the geometric carpet. Jamie follows.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="34716324-b620-44b0-ac5c-3c96761c89ec">
      <SceneProperties Length="2 2/8" Page="39" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAMIE">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAZ">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="KEVIN">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>EXT. PLAYBOY RESORT - POOL DECK - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="bdb283d4-69a5-4acc-a2a8-f5bac81697ec">
      <Text>Kevin at the pool's edge. Chair leg in his hand. Grip adjusting.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f96cb3ee-92f1-443a-a854-ee9f67c394f9">
      <Text>Janet ten feet behind him. Arms crossed. Not against the cold anymore. Just crossed.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="edef6af4-9117-491e-af39-face43928928">
      <Text>Hunter at the tiki bar. Face down. Breathing.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="db49ca6e-c53d-4857-9989-527b41b7486b">
      <Text>Nobody talking. The specific silence of people who have run out of ways to not say the thing they're not saying.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9b1ec879-0751-4f1e-8a81-70fbe020ec8f">
      <Text>Kevin is facing the building. The full dark scale of it, every window black, every balcony empty. The thing he's confined to.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ced13ddc-3350-498e-bdd3-93fa6c0af7e2">
      <Text>Movement.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5ebc618b-08b5-4fb2-8a87-3922d755f251">
      <Text>Deep inside. Through the glass wall at the far end of the pool deck — he can see into the building, into the edge of it, through the exterior glass and across the pool.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="135e397a-b9dd-4691-8a53-926aba291b55">
      <Text>A light. Small. Phone-screen white. Moving left to right deep in the guts of the structure.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b658a03f-250b-435c-98d2-beef8cddacb9">
      <Text>It blinks out. Something between him and the light— a column, a wall, the architecture of a building he hasn't learned yet— blocking it. Gone for two seconds. Three.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1b9fe7ec-da2c-48f4-9bf6-e163eb67d562">
      <Text>It resurfaces. Closer. Moving with purpose.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a928d6ae-3c72-4ee1-857f-b4ee523ef672">
      <Text>Blinks out again. Closer still when it comes back.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1655d9f4-140d-4604-be02-245a7ca6822d">
      <Text>Kevin shifts his weight. The chair leg comes up— not raised, not swung, just repositioned. He steps to his left. Puts himself between Janet and the building. Between whatever is navigating toward them and the woman he told five minutes ago to find a lawyer.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="532317ec-0fcd-407a-b745-7e59f5032e5a">
      <Text>His body instinctively does it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="491a0c76-072c-4bee-ba49-0b420b36ed8e">
      <Text>Janet sees him do it. Sees what it means. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f330395f-61ea-4292-8849-1dc43ca78c75">
      <Text>The light disappears again. Longer this time. Kevin's grip tightens on the chair leg.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8a623f65-116c-4305-a669-b30141297dc7">
      <Text>Then —</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4d25ce3e-fb82-4ae8-8ff8-4adea2014a37">
      <Text>A sound. Metal on metal. The shriek of a door frame that hasn't moved in years being forced open by someone who doesn't care what it thinks about that. The sound bounces off the pool deck and the green water and comes back wrong, too loud.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e5e1cf71-e564-48cd-bfc6-a336261b5e84">
      <Text>A door — center of the building, elevated patio level above the pool deck — shoves open. Phone light spills out.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ee3eae9c-3573-4515-8338-8727d249e9db">
      <Text>Jaz. Jamie behind her.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="867e9748-6b31-448b-bd9b-915524375d9b">
      <Text>Kevin exhales. The chair leg drops to his side.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="94da750e-5504-40ac-8e57-76dd82100690">
      <Text>Janet's arms uncross. One hand goes to her mouth. Comes back down. She steps forward-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>then catches herself. Stops.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f7109311-1921-416d-b070-d4757b37094e">
      <Text>Jaz is standing on the elevated patio looking down at them. Her boots. Her jacket. Her hair a mess from crawling through bushes and two hundred feet of demolished east wing. She is grinning.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="909c4b98-2cbe-442c-a11b-b13d824f776a">
      <Text>Not smiling. Grinning. Phoenix is right there behind her eyes, vibrating, barely contained.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="2b2a601b-3f9b-45f5-94e6-aebfc23fae53">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="3b353c62-3ea0-4854-a8de-d1cc6f907731">
      <Text>How bad is it in there?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e7ca723d-20e7-41c1-9338-e8d550d3e361">
      <Text>Jaz looks at him. Looks at Janet. Looks at the building behind her-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>the mass of it, the eight stories, the wreckage of the east wing ground floor, the lazy river and the street lamps standing at attention in the moonlight on the third floor of a building that everyone forgot.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="5c41a5c9-12df-42a5-b300-8c509a315896">
      <Text>JAZ</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="abb817da-c4f0-4344-b5bb-a6b14bf21ec1">
      <Text>It's fucking perfect.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="19ab9950-2351-481e-9627-27527070aaf1">
      <Text>Kevin stares at her. He looks at the building. Looks back at his daughter. Tries to reconcile the structure he's been staring at— dark, dead, the architectural equivalent of a body on a slab— with the thing she just said.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="856195b8-95b8-4c10-92c9-5a15ec96ff83">
      <Text>He can't. Not yet.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="82b143a4-416c-49a1-abea-7a209e1a9c40">
      <Text>Jaz turns and walks back through the door. Into the building. Not waiting.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="36ee90d7-7852-4c7a-a59c-de66da491e2b">
      <Text>Janet follows. Moving past Kevin without looking at him. Through the door. Gone.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="cee6086e-5033-4584-a7bc-2a2d54c6c224">
      <Text>Kevin stands there. Pool deck. Chair leg. Monitor blinking green.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="0d895d6a-298d-4ca7-bef8-2337ba87226b">
      <Text>JAMIE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="110c2b6e-5e48-4745-9140-d7bc79b77a12">
      <Text>(to Kevin, heading</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="ff692bd9-9635-4acb-9609-1b261b33314b">
      <Text>toward the tiki bar)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="77255e6c-b349-47f2-92c3-0eb97b7fb4de">
      <Text>I'll get Hunter.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e20e7632-9792-48e8-bb79-a8232c1e778c">
      <Text>Kevin watches Jamie cross to the bar. Watches him shake Hunter's shoulder. Watches Hunter's head come up, confused, already talking.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="48250c03-7b65-42a6-84f6-a100ab15cacc">
      <Text>Kevin looks at the building one more time. Then he drops the chair leg on the pool deck-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>it clatters on the concrete and rolls to the edge of the pool-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>and walks through the door.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="93a45537-8a6a-4420-aafe-6353ac6c712b">
      <SceneProperties Length="7/8" Page="41" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAMIE">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="KEVIN">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - INDOOR POOL ROOM - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="55b63f43-2057-4611-ae95-1353aec1a446">
      <Text>Kevin steps through the door and stops.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="88177163-3944-46d3-9024-757ec2d13ef1">
      <Text>The pool. Half-Olympic. Empty. A concrete basin ten feet deep dropping straight down from the deck in front of him. No water. No ramp. Just a sheer drop to a flat bottom with depth markings on the walls and NO DIVING stenciled at intervals like the building is still worried about liability.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="045dd2c7-7ed7-4c43-91ff-30a5b3144d73">
      <Text>A single metal chair sits on the far deck. No explanation.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a110cae4-fd5d-40b2-a069-6c3592f4efdf">
      <Text>On the far side of the room, to the right— Janet disappearing through a doorway after Jaz. Gone.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="69c3e35f-e0eb-4e96-a66b-ebb2206c6937">
      <Text>Jamie steps in behind Kevin. One hand on Hunter's arm. Hunter upright but only in the most technical sense-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>his feet are moving, his eyes are open, the Jameson is doing the rest.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="1defa146-4f00-4715-aab3-4a2bc5f6a8cf">
      <Text>JAMIE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="d27e98d1-e2e0-462e-bf40-e99058db53f9">
      <Text>The stairs are over there. Come on, Dad.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ffc66524-5156-4948-ac38-540aba2be483">
      <Text>Jamie crosses the pool deck, towing Hunter. Hunter's feet find a rhythm that approximates walking.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c136a7a8-48a1-4970-89fa-38aab20b6f5d">
      <Text>Kevin doesn't move. He's looking up. Through the glass wall on the upper section of the far side-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>the interior glass, separating this room from whatever is beyond it-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>moonlight. The pale blue glow of the building's deeper interior. Something enormous in there, lit from above.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1f3f0792-95c5-4872-af80-929209e076b4">
      <Text>He follows his son and his lawyer across the pool deck.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="27ca4b4e-a4c2-4e3e-aec3-6f11d328d8fc">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="982c953d-9b74-47f4-b69f-0fa507c2b853">
      <Text>(to no one)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="798ac4c8-7906-499d-b8ed-164ad79187db">
      <Text>What the fuck are we doing.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7a16b635-eb4c-4fd7-9010-123920a6876b">
      <Text>He shakes his head and takes the stairs.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="28dabf7a-3ce3-493d-b2c4-60b84dc3ecda">
      <SceneProperties Length="2 3/8" Page="42" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="HUNTER">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAZ/PHOENIX">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - THIRD FLOOR CORRIDOR / SIDEWALK CAFÉ - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6529969b-bf51-4fd7-8db7-9731674ee6dd">
      <Text>Kevin comes out from the stairway. The geometric carpet hits him first— green and beige and brown, diamonds inside diamonds, relentless under the phone light Jamie is holding behind him.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4c84ae52-a3ca-426e-a120-a3d18280e7b4">
      <Text>He looks across the wide corridor.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ce38d77b-e54c-4507-8c32-c5d789817ff6">
      <Text>The wide shaft of moonlight.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="290bef9d-c699-4432-9fe6-9677b14e73c9">
      <Text>The Sidewalk Café. The glass ceiling 3 stories up. The wicker chairs and the tables and the wrought iron lamps and the tree.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0112700e-052d-4a10-a911-8d4c29c8fc98">
      <Text>And his daughter. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0112700e-052d-4a10-a911-8d4c29c8fc98">
      <Text>Sitting in a wicker chair. Feet up on a four-top. Dead center of a shaft of moonlight falling through the glass above like a spotlight she called in herself. Thick layer of dust on everything— the table, the chair arms, the surface her boots are resting on— and she could not give less of a shit. She is sitting in it like a throne.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3afd0c2b-28c9-4299-9b6e-ed9430cb0143">
      <Text>Janet is there too. Standing near the stone wall. In the moonlight. Somehow— not touching anything. Present but elevated. Existing on a plane where dust and grime and the accumulated neglect of a dead resort simply do not touch her. Her clothes are the same clothes she was arrested in. She looks great in the moonlight. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="36f5e595-0323-4ab8-8063-60451d2c4fb2">
      <Text>Hunter is draped over the wrought iron railing that lines the lazy river channel. Head down. One hand on the rail, one hand over his eyes. The green tile of the dry river bed below him. The geometric carpet behind him. His body is rejecting the visual information from multiple directions at once.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="479d09fb-ffce-46bb-9cbe-988fe9e5f04e">
      <Text>HUNTER</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="d7ca3f5d-a2d0-4feb-a8c5-6d4c2d4c4d2b">
      <Text>(to the carpet, to God,</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="ee91ce84-484e-4861-a3ba-bf6c44fdd6fa">
      <Text>to whoever is listening)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="e8093c2a-0d72-45c2-9a15-d7f49523e386">
      <Text>Why is it moving like that?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8cce183f-d47b-4a88-a9c2-12ca75608822">
      <Text>Nobody answers him.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2ee035ee-ae12-4884-a410-bea136b778de">
      <Text>Kevin steps into the café. The moonlight catches him. He stops.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e8f5dd29-b56c-4c75-9de2-adde907e8e41">
      <Text>Jaz looks at him.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f556ac56-febd-4c23-b5bb-dccce6705370">
      <Text>He sees Phoenix. The shift happened somewhere between the pool deck when she and Jamie left them outside and this chair. The combat boots on the table. The way she's holding herself— coiled, alert, the girl who floats through a high stakes poker game and doesn't lose.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7f442d2a-3dc3-4945-aa61-4887cb6742fd">
      <Text>She lights a cigarette. The flame illuminates her face. She shakes out the match and the cherry glows in the moonlight.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5196e1bc-4e1a-449a-9592-a9c3b76e5f4a">
      <Text>Kevin looks at her. She looks at him.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="db1d5590-70b4-4dfc-bd3b-3fa4fef932ab">
      <Text>A beat.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e2b156ef-b7aa-4343-a3da-78cd381af96c">
      <Text>They hold it. Father and daughter, seeing each other. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e2b156ef-b7aa-4343-a3da-78cd381af96c">
      <Text>Not the versions they perform at home.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e7468867-1e44-4bd0-bb78-8fc9234f1a89">
      <Text>Kevin assessing: She is not panicked. This is not a teenager in over her head. This is something else.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9cc7dccc-0900-4b63-9476-1bf1216f903a">
      <Text>Phoenix assessing: He is not collapsed. He's lost everything, his wife just detonated under him, and he walked into the building anyway.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9a83b7e2-faa1-4cdc-b1cd-ae702e7e6a6a">
      <Text>Janet shivers. Involuntary. The midnight Jersey highlands night finally finding her.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="29429c91-83ff-42e4-97a1-83e7ed489a27">
      <Text>Kevin reaches for his suit jacket-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>the reflex of twenty-two years, the automatic gesture, already shrugging it off his shoulder-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b3a2eb2e-5bb3-486a-b6b9-3e4d6e55dc3b">
      <Text>He stops.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="cdcafb01-cd98-4341-a977-b8534680312f">
      <Text>She's already wearing Hunter's.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b7befeda-704e-4f26-ace4-94f40a92c87e">
      <Text>Kevin's hand drops. He puts the jacket back on. Looks at the floor. Looks at the carpet. Looks at anything that isn't that.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="fa5f2ec1-4c17-47a9-8baf-7d7e1e0f154e">
      <Text>Phoenix pulls on the cigarette. Exhales. The smoke climbs into the moonlight and disperses against the glass ceiling above.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="a3453bbd-d9cb-44ca-854a-c815b9322a67">
      <Text>Jaz/PHOENIX</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="11968003-47ef-47cf-b2c9-d3708162b9ef">
      <Text>Ok. We need to find out what we're working with. Water. Heat. Sleep. That's tonight. Food is tomorrow.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b08414e9-b3f5-4cea-a92e-80729ddb26fd">
      <Text>She looks at them. Her team. Her father, her mother, her brother holding a phone and a lawyer. The lawyer holding a railing and trying not to die or puke.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d126111e-b32a-4034-905c-d6397d7386b5">
      <Text>She looks at the space around them. The corridor stretching in both directions. The doors. The rooms behind the doors. The kitchens and the offices and the seven hundred other spaces in this building that she hasn't found yet.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="59d83aec-b6fd-433a-a1ea-29a80524c14f">
      <Text>This is a thing she's got.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="0a66f013-99a2-4621-85a0-6a895297bdc1">
      <Text>Jaz/PHOENIX</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="959a7817-6ac4-4634-9281-961bf8005c48">
      <Text>I'll scout. Stay here. Don't get lost.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c14e0e83-d2c9-4cf9-b1b1-791b30729027">
      <Text>She stands. Takes the cigarette with her. Walks into the dark corridor past the street lamps and the planters and the repeating carpet.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f310b273-d558-4fec-bd7c-c875abb61c2d">
      <Text>The glow of the cherry moves with her. Orange point in the dark. It passes a planter. Passes a lamp. Gets smaller.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="65286ab8-9824-4f56-80be-c6b7249a4f83">
      <Text>Her shape is long gone before the cherry is.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="1db77c4a-112e-4672-887c-489627a4f71d">
      <SceneProperties Length="3/8" Page="44" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats/>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PRUITT'S BEDROOM - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c5ed8457-b83e-496a-87bb-daac3ad9633b">
      <Text>Pruitt on his back. Eyes open staring at Rorschach of the ceiling water stain. The TV throwing blue light across the room. Some infomercial. A man selling something with too many attachments.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="64c26948-754c-41b1-8859-d759cad5e9e8">
      <Text>He turns over. Turns back. The sheets are thin and carry a stains caused by solo acts that aren't sleep.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="01319960-3ad6-45b2-b10e-d68e62135c5d">
      <Text>The monitor on the desk glows beside the TV. Janet's mugshot. Zoomed in. Her face filling the screen.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="27344bb8-031e-4d56-b637-bea3b3beb65e">
      <Text>He throws off the blanket.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="d821c8af-d213-4f36-8d69-ac14fda946d1">
      <SceneProperties Length="2/8" Page="44" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats/>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PRUITT'S LIVING ROOM - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="120bdda5-e4b3-415a-ac65-b38232893e6c">
      <Text>Briefs and socks, nothing else. He pads through the living room. His mother in the La-Z-Boy. Housecoat. Mouth open. The chair reclined to its full extension. An oxygen concentrator hums on the floor beside her. Compression sock holding the lymphedema that has swollen her ankles to 9 times their natural size. She doesn't move.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="4d902e35-4f21-4972-83b1-ab7583837bc2">
      <SceneProperties Length="4/8" Page="45" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="PRUITT">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PRUITT'S KITCHEN - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="242cfe05-8a42-4a30-bbf2-87f94b5a27f3">
      <Text>The sink. Dishes stacked past the rim. Plates and mugs and pans in a compressed geology of mold and crust. A coffee cup near the top has something growing in it that has committed to being green.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="28188c58-8165-4b4b-bce0-d90114c37858">
      <Text>He opens the fridge. The light catches his face. He grabs a can of beer. Cracks it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="0a86c0a2-1e12-4c45-a65d-fc5c33398172">
      <Text>PRUITT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="66476872-aaed-4b5e-b010-42dc9a50e3c7">
      <Text>(quiet, to the sink,</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="71a916c5-2c54-42f5-871d-f3b63871682f">
      <Text>to the apartment, to her)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="3c45f9e8-f925-4579-ba4b-a47a4d278979">
      <Text>Stupid cunt could clean up once in a while. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="16f0c6b8-eb1d-4ba4-81d0-8d5ebfeb0b2c">
      <Text>(loudly to the other room)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="3c45f9e8-f925-4579-ba4b-a47a4d278979">
      <Text>That's what loving mothers fucking do.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3eeb5de5-7090-4e32-b825-caab2d370d38">
      <Text>He drinks. Wipes his mouth with the back of his hand.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="d589bbcb-1e24-4cd1-a91d-4248780bad94">
      <SceneProperties Length="4/8" Page="45" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="PRUITT">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PRUITT'S BEDROOM - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3d71c087-7c1b-40d8-88a1-2a71d1fa1dec">
      <Text>He steps back in. The TV. The monitor. The two light sources painting the room in competing frequencies of blue.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4e77114a-f4d8-4057-8824-7cb97623e585">
      <Text>Janet's face on the screen. He stops. Beer in hand.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2aa6db35-0309-40df-bcd2-a1ad6cc6a82b">
      <Text>The mugshot. The booking number across the bottom. Her eyes.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="aa8ec349-2cd4-45ac-80cb-46f97976a883">
      <Text>PRUITT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="a81c9065-4115-4eb2-bdca-aa0346568f77">
      <Text>(soft, different voice entirely)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="ad2028e2-14e5-4ac1-805d-1d3e834b68a2">
      <Text>Soon my love. Just be patient.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8a8c956e-3869-47b7-ac9e-cb860cc5def8">
      <Text>He picks up the flower-print panties from the desk. The fabric dark at the center. Damp. Already soiled from earlier. He holds them for a moment. Looks at her face on the screen.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f8bc90e1-9588-4efa-8584-ca17fe73747d">
      <Text>Takes them to bed.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="f6be3a23-db0d-49f7-88e0-cb48627af37b">
      <SceneProperties Length="3/8" Page="45" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats/>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - FIRST FLOOR - BASEMENT LEVEL - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="1f770cc4-5651-46a2-8f50-dab5b3dbfb88">
      <Text>Phoenix in the guts. Phone light. The walls down here are painted cinder block — beige over grey over whatever came first. Pipe runs along the ceiling. Everything labeled with stenciled letters that assumed someone would always be here to read them.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="cc002b97-fe7b-4ac2-8d47-ecdd120887e1">
      <Text>She follows the corridor. Past the kitchen — massive, stainless steel surfaces reflecting her phone light back at her in cold flashes. Past storage rooms. Past a door marked EMPLOYEE CAFETERIA.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e33fc2aa-5c7f-4e16-94e1-78683e575360">
      <Text>A set of double doors. She pushes through.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="875aa3bb-e9a5-40c8-a2ab-5a4c81742676">
      <SceneProperties Length="1 2/8" Page="46" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats/>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - LAUNDRY - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="62bbe57a-8f8d-43e5-a812-0aab0d8d4df3">
      <Text>She stops.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="704098ec-d738-43bd-abef-f1ec12b809d9">
      <Text>Industrial washers. Industrial dryers. Folding stations. Sorting bins. Massive rolling carts on casters. The room is huge — and at first it reads as chaos, machines crammed into every available square foot like someone lost control of procurement.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4f5756c1-5c0b-47da-bd36-d68d3d916503">
      <Text>Then her eye adjusts. The phone light moves across the space and the logic reveals itself. Intake to wash to dry to fold to sort to cart to out. Every machine placed for the person who would be standing at the one before it. A choreography. A system designed for dozens of people moving through it at speed, feeding and folding for six hundred rooms, every surface positioned so the dance never breaks.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7ce617da-9dd4-4ec7-b686-f7e2d25fcbfd">
      <Text>Phoenix stands in it. Reads it. Respects it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="325cad42-ff1b-41aa-bcfc-4812bd874a7d">
      <Text>She moves deeper. Past the machines. Into the linen storage beyond.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f56970d1-3775-4659-b1ba-03ee68ec12fc">
      <Text>Shelves. Floor to ceiling. Sheets and towels and pillowcases stacked in rows.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6758eee9-7c2d-4940-9c25-c8797b54a486">
      <Text>She pulls one off a shelf. Holds it to her face. Puts it back.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="392f4269-a1aa-4420-b8da-a0ecdb08e943">
      <Text>Musk. Damp. The smell of fabric left too long in a building that breathes moisture and has no one running the air handlers. Organic rot working its way through cotton thread by thread.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7034f124-2e53-435e-a9f2-3f10fbe99ae3">
      <Text>She keeps going. Past the front stock. Into the back storage.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3fd54134-32ae-4534-be8e-3cb1b6a2a6db">
      <Text>Deeper shelves. Darker. The air drier here — interior walls on all sides, no exterior seepage path.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4d632882-7f88-4ed4-bfab-e1c6a4cce3d5">
      <Text>Plastic.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f71425ee-6c89-4241-bab7-ae353760cabc">
      <Text>Sealed plastic. Shipping plastic. Cases of linens still wrapped from the supplier, never opened, never shelved, never rotated into service. Ordered by someone and delivered to a building that closed before anyone cut them open.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3f322755-dc6f-4bc5-9693-729020fcc70f">
      <Text>She tears a corner of plastic off a case. Pulls a blanket out. Holds it to her face.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b02bab9b-b856-4702-9467-0840a3ab0411">
      <Text>Clean. Sealed-air clean. The flat neutral nothing-smell of factory packaging.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f99938c5-1ff7-415f-b1f8-a10016b0c21f">
      <Text>She grabs a rolling cart. Pulls it over. Starts loading. Blankets. Pillows — still in plastic, still compressed into tight vacuum-sealed bricks. More blankets. She stacks the cart until it's top-heavy and doesn't care.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="89c0756a-7855-4da3-937e-3e5ef6bcfbab">
      <Text>She wheels it toward the door. One bad caster pulling left. She kicks it straight.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="dbcced3c-772d-4a36-a766-91cd97679632">
      <Text>The cart rattles through the laundry. Past the machines. Past the choreography of the laid out machines. Into the corridor. Toward the stairs.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="fc559ad8-1fbd-48e2-8561-ae85f5d9d244">
      <SceneProperties Length="1 6/8" Page="47" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="DIANA">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="SARA">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. APARTMENT BUILDING - HALLWAY - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8cadc191-0945-4652-996a-e85abe9791ed">
      <Text>The elevator opens. Diana steps out. Heels on tile. The hallway is— aggressively, judgmentally quiet.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c60dae53-8068-4185-865d-a468f7d146cb">
      <Text>She looks at her phone. 1 AM. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d1ee9b19-b69e-4603-ae5e-34584c94e0ba">
      <Text>Sara's last text. 11:47 PM. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d1ee9b19-b69e-4603-ae5e-34584c94e0ba">
      <Text>"Don't bother tonight. I guess this means you just don't care about him either."</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="244579c1-1421-482c-9b19-99df67daa809">
      <Text>An hour and fifteen minutes ago.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b4a8aea3-45c0-43f7-ba79-938dd532b1b6">
      <Text>Diana stands in the hallway. The apartment door thirty feet away. She doesn't move toward it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="797c0f1f-b29b-4c41-84d2-35ddf61076d3">
      <Text>Doing the math of which is worse. Walking away and be the flake— confirming every accusation Sara has been building the case for since June. Or knocking— and getting the closing argument in person.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7d674e5c-6ca8-45bf-b3e0-04b1285711dd">
      <Text>She reflexively pulls her keys. Crosses to the door. Holds the key up.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="775c5b2b-718e-4163-86e3-77530aaed44d">
      <Text>Stops.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7b498a02-504f-4960-99e0-62f886ffe25e">
      <Text>The key to a door that isn't hers anymore. The propriety of it. The specific wrongness of letting yourself into a place where you are now a visitor settling a little.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c6d90feb-3037-404b-b0f2-f440ecd24512">
      <Text>Before she decides— the door opens.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9ee7c39f-d6dc-4861-acf4-5b283e8a2711">
      <Text>Henri hits her ankles first. Eleven pounds of </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">Shih</Text>
      <Text> </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">Tzu</Text>
      <Text>, zero concept of custody arrangements, pure unregulated joy at the fact that his other mother exists.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="121e8884-ab2a-4ce7-b1ec-ac6f26ff1ee5">
      <Text>Diana crouches. Henri climbs her. She lets him.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c30550d6-1d3a-4678-9eed-bf626efbb23e">
      <Text>Sara in the doorway. Leaning on the frame. Arms crossed. The posture of a woman who has been waiting exactly long enough to have rehearsed what she's going to say and then decided to say something worse.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5ccd3060-6c02-4603-b184-c7994cf4c5fe">
      <Text>Their eyes meet.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b091c41f-7844-4efa-908e-8e5fb200d8cc">
      <Text>Diana opens her mouth.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="8d89aeb5-b2b1-47bc-844a-9fb24401afbc">
      <Text>SARA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="3c046b86-7f47-4b0f-9d9b-9b8d7b42ddde">
      <Text>Don't. I don't need to hear your bullshit. You asked for tonight to be your night with our son.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="75455a71-6f8c-4866-999d-43d94fbcdb6f">
      <Text>She indicates Henri. Henri is licking Diana's wrist.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="285cbc74-c684-4363-8b5a-7d556c2b6f6e">
      <Text>SARA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="5aec1732-016e-44eb-b386-08fe133f6ce2">
      <Text>And you blew more than half of it at work. I have a client meeting at seven tomorrow. I'll expect him back before that.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d71ac124-ed16-4c3a-9ee7-e2f81955af5d">
      <Text>She checks her watch. Precisely. The gesture of someone who bills in five-minute increments.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="3e69c3d0-297d-4d08-be19-1e477fbe0b20">
      <Text>SARA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="3e5166db-4354-4825-ae2b-d9a4f9a80953">
      <Text>That's in just under six hours.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3ab28202-336c-4438-a71e-cd8fcb7a4361">
      <Text>Diana straightens up. Henri in her arms. She doesn't have the energy. She had it once — could match Sara point for point, could hold the line, could fight for the draw. Not tonight. Tonight she has been reading Kevin McCort's financial disclosures for nine hours and she is empty.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="26bd055f-a4e2-45d7-81ea-1d0c6eb1e486">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="2cbaf0f0-2bdf-4109-851a-c8fa8222cf73">
      <Text>Ok. Can I at least come in and get a clean change of clothes? I didn't have time to —</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="235e4a0a-c3f9-4650-b91a-0beb129ef89a">
      <Text>A bag hits the floor. Pre-packed. Zipped. The bag of a woman who knew exactly how tonight would go and prepared accordingly.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e58023b5-bf76-4a21-94da-80f94e299678">
      <Text>Sara turns. The door closes. The lock engages. The deadbolt follows.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="cf11b817-0f75-4ba9-ace3-43a249c89608">
      <Text>Diana stands in the hallway. Henri in one arm. The bag at her feet.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="4a1a1e5d-fe0c-4d85-8b58-cd013939083d">
      <Text>DIANA</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="0d162a27-418d-4565-88f8-32d8605b21ae">
      <Text>(to Henri, to the door,</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="937b6e81-a2d2-4fc5-807b-47d405963126">
      <Text>to the hallway)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="86f9a054-9d2f-4e37-8329-80870782ca91">
      <Text>So much for till death do us part.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9aa2c521-621a-4ca5-8298-f2256a298d50">
      <Text>Henri licks her chin.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="80cb16e3-3ca4-40c9-a05f-bb2cde7c2025">
      <SceneProperties Length="4 6/8" Page="49" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="CHUCKLES">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="STACY">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. CHUCKLES' APARTMENT - AVENUE D - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="59cbd846-f2a7-407b-82ea-0e621810e946">
      <Text>The apartment. Same one. Same posters. Same couch. Same geography of a life that stopped updating its software around 2008. The Les Paul in the corner by the window.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d836385e-f47e-458c-b8f8-c82fa0f84aab">
      <Text>Chuckles is in the kitchen. Shirtless in just an sagging pair of old </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">tighty</Text>
      <Text> </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">whities</Text>
      <Text>, the Misfits shirt draped over the back of a folding chair. He's at the hot plate making instant coffee, the coke fading from his system has opinions about sleep and is winning. His jaw is doing its thing. The spoon against the mug sounds like a metronome with anxiety.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="01c3fab4-68b6-44cf-badb-37a2028e7fba">
      <Text>STACY is pacing. Not the heroin coast from this morning— that wore off hours ago and her whole nervous system is starting to file complaints. She's in her underwear and one of his flannels, unbuttoned, moving through the apartment with the low-frequency agitation of a woman whose blood chemistry is not happy and no one seems to be solving it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="24b21d27-7392-4ff1-95f8-2ae632afac58">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="363a338b-611c-4075-9fdc-6a7a3fecb1ea">
      <Text>Chuck. Chuck. Are you listening to me?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="baafc5bb-8c61-4225-9446-31f9e4932f57">
      <Text>CHUCKLES</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="d8d45114-2c3b-4d75-945d-d58f0467f535">
      <Text>I'm listening.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="2c3e3c00-8005-48f0-a93c-ab1414f7f02d">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="99e4a34d-a249-4ed0-9277-19d8fd29d6c8">
      <Text>Because I've been talking for like twenty minutes and you're just standing there stirring that shit like it's going to turn into something.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="a1bae1b9-c2a0-4ded-b8f9-c8acf1c79093">
      <Text>CHUCKLES</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="03655c6c-44dd-42de-9cf8-c90c2bc19c1f">
      <Text>I hear you. I just don't have anything right now.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="c57c58a2-e2ae-4303-81ec-c98a810c7b3f">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="cfd655f9-1f9e-443d-a54c-7ffacf006edd">
      <Text>You don't have anything. You don't have anything. You ALWAYS have something. Call Declan. Call that kid on Rivington with the backpack—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="17fa2d6b-fd3a-4cb1-a440-9654f0a284be">
      <Text>CHUCKLES</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="da81385d-67d2-4820-a898-0198e003c60f">
      <Text>I'm tapped. I told you I'm tapped.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="725e303c-f932-43c7-819f-23ec442ba2a6">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="38e45c08-18db-4954-8316-92ead7941685">
      <Text>Then get un-tapped. Figure it out. You know everyone? Every booker, every band, every dealer from here to </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">Bushwick</Text>
      <Text> — that's your whole thing, Chuck. That's literally the only thing you are go—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="07c4ad32-88d0-4c7f-82db-b236ca98eefb">
      <Text>She catches herself. Or doesn't. The sentence hangs there, filleted and honest, and Chuckles absorbs it with a flinch.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="c38bd03f-e500-4704-b42e-ba78b711c410">
      <Text>CHUCKLES</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="8e9257a2-8cdd-45b1-8146-d8a93a742e54">
      <Text>(quiet)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="70b0a4dd-abbe-4607-8ea6-af4dd8578772">
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">Stace</Text>
      <Text>— I'll make some calls in the morning. First thing.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="766a0d1d-cdf3-4b92-9532-a1b1ee52dd43">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="ca67a1da-ef09-4969-93ba-d9471604c15f">
      <Text>Don't "</Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">Stace</Text>
      <Text>" me. I'll be sick by morning.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5bb50a76-2b50-461c-9917-fe242af663f1">
      <Text>He puts the mug down. Crosses to her. Puts his hands on her shoulders hoping the fastest route through one of these cycles is physical contact and gentle capitulation.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="3f303fe0-9fd9-4ced-80f4-29fad0c9cb9c">
      <Text>CHUCKLES</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="fc7a0845-fd57-40ca-a653-1453ed8c335e">
      <Text>I know. And I'm going to figure it out. Okay? I promise. Just— sit down. Drink some water. Let me think.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d299418d-64a8-4c07-aacc-f8eb5fb68c16">
      <Text>She settles slightly. Not calm. Paused.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c1a1b713-fc71-4537-a6be-1786a1af3708">
      <Text>Chuckles moves into the bedroom. Opens the nightstand. Nothing. Opens the closet, checks a jacket pocket. Nothing. He's making a show of the visible evidence of effort on her behalf.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5dd06cb5-2723-4022-b2a7-a7a585a8356a">
      <Text>Stacy follows him. She can't sit still.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="90700848-19fc-4ca6-a3a8-c8e1d75bc92e">
      <Text>She starts opening things. The nightstand drawer he already checked— she checks it again, deeper, pulling it all the way out. She opens the small dresser against the wall. Socks. Boxers. A ConEd bill from 2019. She closes it. Opens the next one.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="47e3502a-c7f3-423a-81a8-64335f3c0a9c">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="ad4f24ed-f0a7-41fb-8fb8-c3301642f902">
      <Text>You have to have something we can sell. What's in here?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="9e21cdc1-cb4c-4165-a52e-6b4d8c4d24e5">
      <Text>She's pulling at the bottom drawer now. Hard. It sticks. She yanks it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e19a43d8-3225-43fa-89c1-3ea018ee863e">
      <Text>She's already looking at the bed. At the mattress. At the space between the mattress and the box spring where people keep things.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="73169ab8-6893-489f-ba44-e94aa517471e">
      <Text>She slides her hand under.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="006ad4ae-d4bf-42ea-8517-f762e9aee95c">
      <Text>CHUCKLES</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="a8f630f0-053a-4be1-b943-9c81d3d336cb">
      <Text>Don't—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b231d5c9-ed18-411b-98c9-e7f5b4173dd2">
      <Text>She pulls.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c8114bed-af77-49b3-8e12-06b2d15cd82b">
      <Text>Record sleeves. Old ones. The cardboard soft at the corners from decades of careful handling. She fans them on the bed. Eight. Nine. She pulls until there's nothing left.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="83d250ba-4230-4976-a8c6-22bfee355326">
      <Text>She flips one over. Squints at it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="d7c7c90f-e846-4a8f-8f34-e4e5a8b96623">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="def8ec87-1277-42b6-912e-3022fff54919">
      <Text>What is this, big band? Sinatra?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="138d48fe-2985-4211-aff4-411d5ffef2fb">
      <Text>(looking at him)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="a7268764-0c78-4c4c-9e31-852b6a30c29d">
      <Text>Are you serious right now?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="523f5736-c1ba-491a-b10d-6daae6baf581">
      <Text>CHUCKLES</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="1d5a878b-ff2a-48f2-8924-4b19306ca7ea">
      <Text>Put them back.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="5a723a6c-11b2-40c0-b708-e0a2eb6e3f26">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="7e12054e-6978-4ff2-b1af-762595af1fc5">
      <Text>Some of these look old, Chuck. Like actually old. And this one is signed. We could get—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="ba88b88a-0b24-4b76-80fa-4c474bea6907">
      <Text>CHUCKLES</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="9580a4f1-5080-4609-85b1-594d67ff3c42">
      <Text>They were my father's. Put them back.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7ae73db8-62dd-46d2-8a27-7583cecf679c">
      <Text>Something in his voice. Not the coke voice. Not the grinding rapid-fire pivot voice. Something underneath. Something actually solid.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f47786ef-6400-4ebd-8c6b-7d2ca44ef358">
      <Text>She looks at his face. She puts the records on the bed. Not gently. Not violently. The middle ground of a woman is to push without losing meal ticket.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="c70fe46c-33a4-4196-919f-38d2889d3a3a">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="2548e013-f039-4f1c-a13e-6a037f246dbd">
      <Text>Fine. Fine. Your daddy's pussy lounge music records. Off limits. I get it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="31611768-bbbb-49dc-b9b5-aa7aaaf68511">
      <Text>She walks back into the front room. Pacing. The agitation climbing again. She's running out of drawers and out of patience and the sickness is coming up the back of her throat like a tide.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4fa3fcda-d9de-4232-91d3-1001c47e0f67">
      <Text>Her eyes move through the apartment. The posters with pin holes. The hot plate. The mug.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3dfde505-3bbd-48fb-975a-347a1d137773">
      <Text>The guitar.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e330aab3-5c1c-477c-a6a7-d63b68937b68">
      <Text>She crosses to the corner. Reaches for the neck of the Les Paul.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="e8cffc8b-8e9d-4ea6-8948-9907cc0ac066">
      <Text>CHUCKLES</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="3dd6ddfc-32a0-4d10-9f0b-d53109bb418a">
      <Text>(from the bedroom doorway— fast, clear, the clearest thing he's said all night)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="372303c3-ce9e-428f-8883-bf8c2e9b0648">
      <Text>Don't touch it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="1758f629-06c8-40d4-8eb3-a05e71894c99">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="8c17a879-4a8a-4779-9c1c-9859862d80a3">
      <Text>(hand still out)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="301c8a3d-dfd9-4692-bed7-42e94ceaf3e5">
      <Text>Chuck, this is a vintage Gibson. This is worth—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="3e2c5167-a378-427e-80b1-891b486f0305">
      <Text>CHUCKLES</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="54a6ba7d-0557-4e18-af9f-c74721b774c6">
      <Text>That is my father's guitar. It is not for sale. It is not for trade. It does not leave that stand.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="aa5db875-830f-4df4-a9b0-9192abf0ebf5">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="4fd9eb72-f5c2-44a0-ab31-375111161d69">
      <Text>Your father's guitar. Your father's records. Your father's, your father's— what in this apartment is actually YOURS that is worth something, Chuck?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="c84b2641-eda1-4ef8-bd04-4620ad11df5a">
      <Text>CHUCKLES</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="1eb12879-1e7e-4a4a-97cb-049816913722">
      <Text>(very still)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="81749047-b611-4e55-8900-00fce047189e">
      <Text>Nothing, there's nothing left.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d0e837e1-af9b-4421-ad72-716834b3ef46">
      <Text>The room holds it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="94dafcee-7e2f-4bf4-9450-e9df09ce5b74">
      <Text>Stacy's hand is still near the neck of the Les Paul. She's calculating. An addict measuring the distance between what she needs and what's standing in the way of it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="fa46d579-a181-4f9d-9ea0-0818b0f67f4f">
      <Text>She looks at him. At his face. At whatever is behind his face right now.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="38074ec1-076d-4624-b29d-d44c809770fb">
      <Text>She can't use this version of him. Her hand drops.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="b7fe7874-74d5-4fc4-b744-30acd641d544">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="7e774064-24a8-4cd5-bc99-1e56ca5e0137">
      <Text>(getting dressed, fast — pulling on jeans, looking for her shoes)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="042d4fae-4ad8-4367-838f-b1a27b021571">
      <Text>You know what, Chuck? Fuck you. Fuck your dad. And fuck Frank Sinatra. If you can't even— if you won't even try to—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ee9ffecd-e183-4ea2-bb14-ddf01781c150">
      <Text>She finds one shoe. Jams her foot in.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="70bab8f8-9f61-4d94-86c1-49fd43a784f5">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="19a45c24-e381-4445-8253-d5b09d7350d7">
      <Text>I came here because you said you'd take care of me. That's the deal. I come here, I stay, I let you cum in whatever hole of mine you fucking feel like, and you take care of me. And you can't even do that. You can't even sell one fucking record for—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8e1b79ab-576e-41f3-8562-89a8524a517f">
      <Text>She finds the other shoe.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="279eacfd-8dad-459c-b9d4-41bb1692545e">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="067d09d7-ec58-47c8-bfbb-e4bd963e3d2b">
      <Text>You want to sit here and cry like a bitch over a dead man's shit while I'm dying? Fine. Do it alone.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8fcde628-d318-4328-b495-8da07fdf62a1">
      <Text>She grabs her jacket off the couch. Checks the pockets-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>force of habit, always checking pockets. She's at the door.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="e67b0b18-ec7d-41cd-9b0b-ef8909b79565">
      <Text>STACY</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="4ba30552-02aa-44fb-8b5e-98842ba3b345">
      <Text>(turning back, one last shot)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="c8ad077c-c08b-439d-baff-76fd6505ce16">
      <Text>You know what you are? You're a soft little pussy boy who's still living in his shit hole apartment crying over his daddy's guitar listening to his pussy daddy's sleaze ball music, while you walk around this neighborhood in combat boots pretending you're Johnny Rotten. And that's the saddest shit I've ever seen in my life.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7473ac32-5009-4cb3-bc07-3add5dfc5b9a">
      <Text>The door opens. Closes. Her boots in the stairwell. Getting fainter. Gone.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6a9a0298-da87-487a-8d3e-2674bec209fc">
      <Text>Chuckles stands in the apartment. He walks to the corner. Checks the guitar on the stand. Adjusts the neck. A quarter inch. It didn't need adjusting.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f55852e4-465b-4319-901b-83264a1b57ff">
      <Text>He goes to the bedroom. Puts the records back under the mattress. One at a time. In order. The way they go.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="bb9ab2b7-952f-488e-ba59-dcfdf883c827">
      <SceneProperties Length="3 4/8" Page="53" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAMIE">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="JAZ/PHOENIX">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
          <CharacterArcBeat Name="KEVIN">
            <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="0.00" OutlineLevel="0" RightIndent="1.39" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No"/>
          </CharacterArcBeat>
        </SceneArcBeats>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - SIDEWALK CAFÉ / THIRD FLOOR CORRIDOR - NIGHT</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="279ee1a1-3ff7-41d8-9dab-304eabf8e57a">
      <Text>Phoenix rounds the corner pushing the cart. One bad caster. The rattle echoing down the corridor.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b2786cef-d385-47c6-a8d8-ef8d1ded5bbf">
      <Text>The café is empty. But from deeper in the building — down the corridor toward the lobby — shuffling. Movement. The sounds of people trying to be useful in a place they don't understand yet.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c7ba2027-a1ac-4b1b-b495-db86b036a090">
      <Text>She follows it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="61d0e3af-1fd2-477b-96d3-c70ec9b03865">
      <Text>The corridor opens. The ceiling lifts again — but different this time. Not the glass panes of the café. This is the atrium. The main lobby. The ceiling climbs three full stories through stepped tiers of pink-accented balconies and river rock walls, each level receding inward, ferns and ivy trailing from planters on every tier — some dead, some impossibly still alive — until the space terminates in a massive skylight at the top. Moonlight falls through it and drops the full height of the atrium onto the lobby floor.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c9bd3014-f7ac-4e72-a6e5-40b41622a3f6">
      <Text>The floor is stone. Blue-grey slate, irregular cuts, cool and hard under her boots after all that carpet.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3486c398-8a74-4d90-9bc0-32f25316228b">
      <Text>And the fireplace.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c030cc54-a9f5-4c8c-a52d-0eecca430e6d">
      <Text>Copper. A single sheet of riveted copper panels climbing the full height of the back wall — three stories of oxidized metal catching the moonlight and throwing it back amber and green. The hearth at its base is wide enough to park a car in, stepped up from the lobby floor on a platform of teal carpet. A striped armchair sits in front of it. Wooden planters with gravel and dead things flank it on both sides.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="507ae00c-661a-4ea4-af42-2fe2d35b4d05">
      <Text>Hunter is in the armchair. The dust cloud around him still thickening, still expanding outward from the impact of his deposit into the cushion. His eyes are closed. His mouth is open. He is asleep in the way that only Jameson and total psychological defeat can produce.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8c3c9320-46f8-430c-9b87-01890e576782">
      <Text>Jamie is in the back corner of the hearth. Crouched. Hands on something. Investigating.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0a15e6f4-3376-49f5-9c5f-7264526e2c0e">
      <Text>Kevin is behind the reception desk. A massive wooden counter running along the far wall. He's pulling drawers. Opening cabinets. Looking for something. He doesn't know what. A flashlight. A map. A manual. Anything that suggests someone left instructions for whatever this is.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2410af88-e490-4ee2-9739-c9aee5d9ab5b">
      <Text>Janet is standing near the fireplace platform. Hunter's jacket on her shoulders. Arms pulled tight inside it. Her shivering has stopped being about temperature and become about everything else. In the moonlight, on the teal carpet, in front of the dead copper fireplace, she looks smaller than Jaz has ever seen her. More alone than should be possible for someone standing in a room with her entire family.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3eea127a-c0ae-468e-b785-a57f1ca7bc83">
      <Text>Jaz parks the cart. Starts pulling plastic-wrapped packages off of it. Tearing the seals. Shaking out blankets.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="1a1d9187-006a-4229-ac60-2b8e83812f7d">
      <Text>JAZ/phoenix</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="b943e6b2-57e1-454d-8032-0fb28a9d5fb0">
      <Text>Well. This is as good a place as any to bed down for the night. Tomorrow's light and a little sleep will make everything easier.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="638ae857-fda9-4519-8547-362db7ff11e9">
      <Text>She stacks blankets on the teal carpet. Drops sealed pillows beside them.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6ca10ab7-b646-423b-be32-4f1a0fd10ff5">
      <Text>Jamie's voice from inside the hearth.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="75fe9ca6-4b90-4c6b-8853-9fee10df0237">
      <Text>JAMIE</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="a97e5d0f-1b47-4179-ab95-f67c1114982d">
      <Text>Do you think the gas is still on?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a95667a8-8d3b-4dff-839b-613c48327537">
      <Text>Jaz pulls her book of matches from her jacket. Strikes one. The flame on her face.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="3cfe15d2-7d7b-47d8-8fe4-36af2064b66d">
      <Text>JAZ/phoenix</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="54f0314e-9c54-47a2-8c9d-3b0381db8924">
      <Text>Would be nice.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5c4e80b8-32c0-4b93-91b7-31906cd962c5">
      <Text>She crouches at the hearth. Holds the match to the lava rocks in the basin. Jamie's hand finds the valve behind the copper housing. He turns it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d19a62d5-a5a8-4d3a-9f28-354093f9cbee">
      <Text>Nothing.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c30b902c-81b0-4fff-89b1-921f95e2523e">
      <Text>The squeak of a mechanism giving up its resistance. Metal on metal. Decades of seized position releasing in increments.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3ce531e9-b221-4ad1-9cbf-e1e99289ac32">
      <Text>A beat.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d6e1dc11-1fff-4c0b-b884-4e47cd635f20">
      <Text>A hiss.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="099535be-987c-4611-b892-4b039b21f833">
      <Text>Then — </Text>
      <Text AdornmentStyle="-1">WHOOOOSH</Text>
      <Text>.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="fb0305bd-4df8-4e92-a1a6-3a51ff4319ec">
      <Text>The flames hit the lava rocks and climb. The copper wall catches the fire and the lobby fills with light-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>warm, orange, alive-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>the hearth throwing heat and glow across three stories of atrium, the balconies above suddenly visible, the ferns casting shadows on pink walls, the skylight reflecting the fire back down into the room.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="947c9c2c-d19d-4cab-b803-2805e4402bf9">
      <Text>The building breathes. Its first breath in years.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="b69548a0-7e35-4252-bb5c-41ada4b08800">
      <Text>KEVIN</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Parenthetical" id="60585536-333f-408f-a1ca-413d0b80b9fe">
      <Text>(from behind the desk, moving)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="67236f28-5900-4dbc-8f9a-435dc0f03446">
      <Text>It's not safe. Shut it down.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="aa40fd1b-b056-4b76-a91e-b7a3a57cc020">
      <Text>Jaz holds up her hand.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="db3d488b-9a9e-4d0c-ad51-5754a7635a6c">
      <Text>Not rude. Not the hand of a teenager defying a parent. The hand of a person with information, asking for a moment to confirm it. The gesture of an equal.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5976bd9f-82e1-40ee-9904-aa893fecbbaa">
      <Text>Kevin stops. Registers it. Something shifts in his face-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>a recognition he was not prepared for and does not have a category for.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="687505ba-aefb-4795-8564-3d111e7cb534">
      <Text>Jaz moves her hand above the flames. Feeling the air. Reading the draw. She moves it higher, near the top of the flame line, feeling for the pull of the chimney.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="51d860f1-4413-43ff-b759-b3695aad2483">
      <Text>JAZ/phoenix</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="8b9b5335-45ce-45e7-85d3-6e8ccbf39f7e">
      <Text>It's venting. The flue is working.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="31eae48a-acd3-4f88-9986-646b24d6e8dc">
      <Text>She holds her hand there. The air moving up and out. The draft steady.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Character" id="a5de83b1-1cc1-4209-9350-bb41140d58da">
      <Text>JAZ/phoenix</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Left" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="2.50" RightIndent="6.00" SpaceBefore="0" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="Dialogue" id="4d01f5ed-2d2e-413b-9e64-5f58e26ff35b">
      <Text>We watch for smoke buildup. But as long as the flow is up and out, we're good.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="103eb188-4225-477a-aa5a-0bb118d5224b">
      <Text>Kevin stands behind the reception desk. His daughter is crouched in front of a fireplace the size of a studio apartment, reading airflow, making structural assessments, and she is correct.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="31a67b52-85de-41de-b5c2-04483cac46b4">
      <Text>He has no response for this.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="58a99440-c647-4c96-a1c3-b9371d89ff49">
      <Text>Janet moves toward the fire. The heat finds her and something releases. Her shoulders drop. Her hands come out of Hunter's jacket for the first time since her arraignment. She opens the jacket. Lets the warmth in. Stands in it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0dd251ef-34cf-4459-89ed-d356d15eea4b">
      <Text>The firelight on the copper wall. The moonlight from above. The two light sources painting the lobby in competing golds.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="58b1880d-b086-4a60-ba4a-8b5566182965">
      <Text>Jaz distributes. Blankets. Pillows. She puts a blanket over Hunter without waking him. He shifts. Doesn't open his eyes.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c9cd142f-6f3a-494d-99c8-b5ef85ec5fd9">
      <Text>She sets a blanket and pillow on the teal carpet near the hearth. Another set across the lobby, near the reception desk.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="7a675fcf-aa3c-41bf-83c3-bd54f8ff9b6e">
      <Text>Kevin looks at the blanket near the desk. Looks at the one near the hearth. Registers the distance between them. The geography of it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="bc4da137-42eb-4515-a27b-a8532881aacc">
      <Text>Janet is already settling near the fire. On the carpet. Wrapping herself in the blanket. Facing the flames.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="07460130-64cf-4a40-8416-d62c8f334383">
      <Text>Kevin takes the one by the desk. Sits on the stone floor. Leans against the wood paneling. Pulls the blanket across his legs.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="069fb4ac-ecd3-45f3-a829-234ebfeff07e">
      <Text>Twenty feet between them. The lobby. The firelight. The copper wall.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="02356954-3a51-4b7d-a688-df59499363f1">
      <Text>Jamie finds a spot on the hearth platform. Curls up. Phone still in his hand, screen dimming, dimming, going dark.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0471c2f4-52f8-446d-881a-edbe95ee13ca">
      <Text>Jaz is the last one standing. She looks at them. Her family. Arranged across the lobby of a dead resort in the firelight like figures in a painting nobody commissioned. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0471c2f4-52f8-446d-881a-edbe95ee13ca">
      <Text>Her father against the desk. Her mother by the hearth. Her brother on the platform. Her lawyer in a chair.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="60d50fa1-d181-4aed-b657-5d4b6f152a28">
      <Text>The fire has settled. Low orange on the lava rocks.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="73cc03c5-95f3-407f-a512-0d8f77f73d81">
      <Text>She looks at the stairwell, eyes following up into the darkness.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="18ded1cf-4e80-4871-a37f-c24f193023ef">
      <SceneProperties Length="1" Page="57" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats/>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - FIFTH FLOOR MEZZANINE - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="3922c1cd-b431-4712-af5a-33b12b48966d">
      <Text>Jaz emerges up the staircase, moves to the railing of the mezzanine. Below, two stories down— the lobby floor. The copper fireplace. Her family small in the firelight. Safe for now.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5e8796ee-efea-4338-8f65-68a8d270c898">
      <Text>She lights another cigarette. Turns. Her eyes sparking with the mystery and promise of this place.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6392313e-4e7a-44a6-833a-931ecc4e74ed">
      <Text>The corridor runs ahead into the dark. She pulls her phone. The beam arcs out into the void around her.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="a89db3cb-dd60-4130-a0ca-39e7f8e45b29">
      <Text>The ballroom opens around her— the ceiling pulling back and away, the space too large to resolve all at once. The original 1970s ballroom lighting hanging dead above it. The stage at the far end, the parquet dance floor like it's been waiting for someone to show up.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2f300201-de45-4272-8862-124bb2eb64ef">
      <Text>The place is enormous.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ac0b1b0a-a447-42bf-b41c-f16408e8a012">
      <Text>Something pulls her back. A hint. A hunch. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="6b093c31-986c-4c12-af63-9bd9baf5f6e6">
      <Text>She turns back, staring deep down the mezzanine corridor.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2c44e305-349d-4e09-80ca-8b564165e06b">
      <Text>The railing on her left. The corridor stretching down passed the Sidewalk Café glass roof mezzanine railing, moonlight falling through it. Shafts of moonlight raking on the geometrics of the carpet until finally fading into the infinity of darkness.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ba40c66b-7c7a-4cdd-89b3-1408332d9c63">
      <Text>And there-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="5362ec1c-0568-4dee-ba5f-562a526cb0c3">
      <Text>Above the double doors at the corridor's end — a white plaque. Simple. The moonlight from the café's skylight finding it through the railing in pale silver.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="8be17655-90d7-4fd6-8fb6-701e5a258246">
      <Text>CABARET.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f9330288-2248-4bef-bc9e-b68d63c6cc63">
      <Text>She stares at it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4127c11e-7392-4100-84b5-54aeb417d0e0">
      <Text>Then-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="053bc1a6-6d94-4526-9b3a-81eec921f548">
      <Text>Her feet move before she decides. One step. Two. Then faster. The boots on the carpet running— </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="053bc1a6-6d94-4526-9b3a-81eec921f548">
      <Text>The sign getting larger, the doors below it, the doors—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="f8084b23-a9b8-4b5d-9fa2-ab1f457d816a">
      <Text>Full tilt-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="769378af-c180-483a-8a8e-c42c55447357">
      <Text>She hits them with both hands.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Transition" id="baa744d7-2228-4d76-835d-63cddb67191f">
      <Text>Cut to BLACK:</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Scene Heading" id="e20d5c15-3567-4dd5-88c0-a9108075f3e9">
      <SceneProperties Length="1 2/8" Page="58" Title="">
        <SceneArcBeats/>
      </SceneProperties>
      <Text>INT. PLAYBOY RESORT - CABARET - CONTINUOUS</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="2de3e2e6-8408-4447-b98f-28b03d203349">
      <Text>A beat. Two.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="4acc2f4e-5711-44f5-a777-097a0728b873">
      <Text>Then light erupts through the seams of the doors — moonlight flooding the gaps, the frame blazing white as the doors blow open from within—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="ec0e3a93-717e-4416-b860-58d8e3274ca4">
      <Text>Jaz carved in hard silhouette. The moonlight shaft streaming outlining her in the dark of the room.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="c38770af-3b98-4bf5-9747-108ae77abd78">
      <Text>The camera moves around her, past her, turning to reveal—</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="dd1e4f20-ef3a-4159-8b8b-8050ce7c6e03">
      <Text>1972. Original. Hugh Hefner's Cabaret.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="41c0f037-9995-49d9-8bce-05cceebae0ba">
      <Text>Three tiers of black and red leather U-shaped booths stepping down toward the central dance floor. not cracked, not separating at the seams— intact. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="41c0f037-9995-49d9-8bce-05cceebae0ba">
      <Text>Every sight line perfect, every seat in the house looking at the stage. The split-level stage, the rigging above it, the motorized foreground frozen mid-position on its last cue. </Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="41c0f037-9995-49d9-8bce-05cceebae0ba">
      <Text>The lighting grid. The glass control booth at the back. The full bar behind it, bottles long gone, the brass rail still running its length.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="cf266a23-fa9e-48de-b266-7c68d6f006b2">
      <Text>Enormous. Beautiful. A complete catastrophe.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="334a06a3-14ac-4dab-bd91-f773bbbdb7ba">
      <Text>The most perfect thing she has ever seen.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="63e5fbc8-9343-4fdb-80c6-ebbb9877544d">
      <Text>She descends. Each step on the tiered stairway landing under her boot like its welcoming her home.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="0c8ba996-dd32-4ee3-8584-27ba34bfe056">
      <Text>Her boots hit the dance floor.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="29b087a6-5361-43bd-8f74-d609e29f9f83">
      <Text>The sound of it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="da567dfa-51f6-4419-b799-4ff26d9377a0">
      <Text>Phoenix stands in the center of the Playboy Cabaret. The moonlight shaft falling long across the wood beneath her. The tiers rising on three sides. The stage ahead.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="d7679586-1309-4320-8cee-75f9b8c2afcb">
      <Text>The tears come. The moonlight holds her.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="14cb2611-d118-492c-bf01-685bd7ffa400">
      <Text>She stands in the heart of it. Face open. Unperformed. Home.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="b0efc507-ca70-4d6c-ba6c-e1343bd9909b">
      <Text>She pulls her phone.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="aad8545a-db7d-4a1e-aaf1-50d43aea29d9">
      <Text>The screen light on her wet face. She types.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="85335a00-8ee2-44ce-8192-5087eb9775c2">
      <Text>JAZ (TEXT to Chuckles): I found it. Meet me here as soon as you can.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="74328ff1-4db1-4ed6-bc27-f773bb4916a0">
      <Text>She drops a pin.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="40002eba-1085-4e55-984e-ee9e3f0ef141">
      <Text>Her thumb hovers. She looks up-</Text>
      <Text Font="Sans Devanagari Final Draft"> </Text>
      <Text>at the stage, at the rigging, at the ghost of the lighting grid above her. At all of it.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="e350d84a-f476-461a-821c-fe3a02285607">
      <Text>She hits send.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action" id="787ae6b1-ebc4-4588-82c1-8282b4a21837">
      <Text>The screen blinks out and we-</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Transition" id="381826b5-be4d-4cbd-8a58-5f86f7b66933">
      <Text>SMASH TO BLACK.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Alignment="Center" FirstIndent="0.00" Leading="Regular" LeftIndent="1.00" RightIndent="7.50" SpaceBefore="24" Spacing="1" StartsNewPage="No" Type="End of Act" id="5c45adea-79f9-4072-a4e1-f79a5dbdf8e2">
      <Text Style="Bold+Underline+AllCaps">END OF EPISODE THREE.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
  </Content>

